INSERT INTO `thesis_sections` VALUES (1,'abstract',NULL,NULL,'Abstract','<div class=\"thesis-abstract\">\n<p><strong>Background:</strong> Small and Medium Enterprises (SMEs) face increasing cybersecurity threats, with SSH-based attacks representing a significant attack vector. Traditional security solutions like fail2ban provide threshold-based protection but cannot detect sophisticated attack patterns or novel threats.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Objective:</strong> This research develops SSH Guardian, an open-source, ML-enhanced SSH security framework that combines traditional rule-based detection with machine learning anomaly detection and third-party threat intelligence integration to provide comprehensive protection suitable for resource-constrained SME environments.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Methods:</strong> Following Design Science Research methodology, we developed a three-layer detection architecture: (1) rule-based threshold detection compatible with fail2ban, (2) Isolation Forest machine learning for unsupervised anomaly detection, and (3) integration with AbuseIPDB, VirusTotal, and GeoIP services. The system was evaluated using the CICIDS2017 dataset and real production deployment data.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Results:</strong> The hybrid detection approach achieved an F1-score of 0.91, outperforming rule-only (0.82) and ML-only (0.87) configurations. The system successfully detected distributed attacks (76% detection) and slow brute force attempts (81% detection) that evade traditional threshold-based detection, while maintaining low false positive rates (1.2%).</p>\n\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> SSH Guardian demonstrates that hybrid detection architectures can significantly enhance SSH security for SMEs without requiring extensive resources or expertise. The open-source implementation provides a practical contribution to the cybersecurity community.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Keywords:</strong> SSH security, machine learning, intrusion detection, threat intelligence, SME cybersecurity, Isolation Forest, fail2ban, hybrid detection</p>\n</div>',1,1,1,1,280,'2025-12-06 17:57:44','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(2,'chapter1',NULL,'1','Introduction','<p>The digital transformation of business operations has made information technology infrastructure critical to organizational success. Among the various protocols and services that enable remote administration and secure data transfer, the Secure Shell (SSH) protocol stands as one of the most fundamental yet targeted entry points for cyber attacks. This chapter establishes the research context, presents the problem statement, and outlines the objectives and scope of this study.</p>',10,1,1,1,70,'2025-12-06 17:57:44','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(3,'chapter2',NULL,'2','Literature Review','<h1>Chapter 2: Literature Review</h1>\n\n<p><strong>Keywords:</strong> SSH Security, Intrusion Detection Systems, Machine Learning, Isolation Forest, Anomaly Detection, Threat Intelligence, Hybrid Detection, Cybersecurity, Network Security, Fail2ban, AbuseIPDB, VirusTotal, SME Security</p>\n\n<h2>Chapter Abstract</h2>\n<p>This chapter presents a comprehensive review of the literature related to SSH security, intrusion detection systems, and machine learning approaches for cybersecurity. The review synthesizes findings from 17 primary sources published between 2020-2024, examining traditional rule-based detection methods, machine learning algorithms for anomaly detection, and threat intelligence integration strategies. Key findings indicate that hybrid detection approaches combining rule-based and ML methods achieve 15-35% better detection performance than single-method solutions, while Isolation Forest demonstrates optimal characteristics for network anomaly detection. The chapter concludes with a literature matrix and research gap analysis that establishes the theoretical foundation for the SSH Guardian framework.</p>\n\n<hr/>\n\n<p>The purpose of this literature review is to examine existing research in SSH security, intrusion detection systems, and machine learning-based threat detection. This review establishes the theoretical foundation for the SSH Guardian framework and identifies research gaps that this study addresses (Cao et al., 2023).</p>\n\n<p>The structure of this chapter follows a logical progression: Section 2.1 introduces the SSH security landscape, Sections 2.2-2.3 examine traditional and ML-based detection approaches, Sections 2.4-2.6 provide in-depth analysis of rule-based, ML-based, and hybrid detection systems, Section 2.7 explores threat intelligence integration, Section 2.8 identifies research gaps, and Section 2.9 presents the comprehensive literature summary matrix (Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022).</p>',20,1,1,1,45,'2025-12-06 17:57:44','2025-12-25 10:46:52'),(4,'chapter3',NULL,'3','Methodology and System Design','<p>This chapter presents the research methodology, system architecture, and technical design decisions that guided the development of SSH Guardian. The Design Science Research paradigm provides the overarching framework, while specific sections detail the detection layers, feature engineering, and evaluation approach.</p>',30,1,1,1,50,'2025-12-06 17:57:44','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(5,'chapter4',NULL,'4','Implementation','<p>This chapter details the technical implementation of SSH Guardian, including the backend API, machine learning module, threat intelligence integration, and web dashboard. Code excerpts illustrate key design decisions.</p>',40,1,1,1,35,'2025-12-06 17:57:44','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(6,'chapter5',NULL,'5','Evaluation and Results','<p>This chapter presents the experimental results from evaluating SSH Guardian. We analyze detection performance across configurations, examine real-world deployment data, and compare the hybrid approach against baseline methods.</p>',50,1,1,1,40,'2025-12-06 17:57:44','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(7,'chapter6',NULL,'6','Conclusion and Future Work','<p>This chapter interprets the experimental results, discusses implications for practice, and addresses limitations of the research.</p>',60,1,1,1,20,'2025-12-06 17:57:44','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(8,'ch2_sec4','chapter2','2.4','Rule-Based Intrusion Detection Systems','<h2>2.4 Rule-Based Intrusion Detection Systems</h2>\n\n<p>Rule-based intrusion detection systems (IDS) employ predefined signatures and threshold patterns to identify malicious activity. This section examines prominent rule-based approaches and their applicability to SSH security (Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022).</p>\n\n<h3>2.4.1 Signature-Based Detection</h3>\n\n<p>Signature-based IDS compare network traffic against databases of known attack patterns. Leading solutions include Snort (Ahmad et al., 2021), Suricata (Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022), and OSSEC (Ferrag et al., 2020). These systems excel at detecting known threats but fail against novel attack variants.</p>\n\n<h4>Table 2.2: Rule-Based IDS Comparison</h4>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>System</th><th>Detection Method</th><th>Strengths</th><th>Limitations</th><th>Source</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Snort</td><td>Signature matching</td><td>Extensive rule library; community support</td><td>Requires constant updates; no ML</td><td>Ahmad et al., 2021</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Suricata</td><td>Multi-threaded signatures</td><td>High performance; Lua scripting</td><td>Complex configuration</td><td>Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>OSSEC</td><td>Log analysis + FIM</td><td>Host-based; file integrity</td><td>Limited network visibility</td><td>Ferrag et al., 2020</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Fail2ban</td><td>Threshold counting</td><td>Simple; SSH-specific; integrates with iptables</td><td>23% false positives; reactive only</td><td>Zhang et al., 2022</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>2.4.2 Fail2ban Architecture and Limitations</h3>\n\n<p>Fail2ban remains the most widely deployed open-source SSH protection tool (Zhang et al., 2022). Its architecture comprises three core components:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Filter:</strong> Regex patterns matching authentication failures in /var/log/auth.log</li>\n<li><strong>Jail:</strong> Configuration defining maxretry, findtime, and bantime thresholds</li>\n<li><strong>Action:</strong> Firewall commands (iptables/ufw) executed upon threshold breach</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><strong>Critical Limitations Identified:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Threshold Dependency:</strong> Detection occurs only after maxretry failures (default: 5), allowing attackers up to 4 free attempts (Zhang et al., 2022)</li>\n<li><strong>Static Configuration:</strong> Cannot adapt to emerging attack patterns without manual rule updates (Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022)</li>\n<li><strong>No Behavioral Analysis:</strong> Fails to detect slow, distributed attacks below threshold (Cao et al., 2023)</li>\n<li><strong>False Positives:</strong> Legitimate users with typos are blocked (23% rate per Zhang et al., 2022)</li>\n<li><strong>No Threat Intelligence:</strong> Does not leverage external IP reputation data (Tounsi & Rais, 2020)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>These limitations motivate the hybrid approach implemented in SSH Guardian, which enhances fail2ban with ML scoring and threat intelligence integration (Yang et al., 2023).</p>\n\n<h3>2.4.3 Rule-Based Detection Strengths</h3>\n\n<p>Despite limitations, rule-based systems offer distinct advantages that should be preserved in hybrid architectures (Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Deterministic Behavior:</strong> Predictable blocking decisions aid compliance auditing</li>\n<li><strong>Low Latency:</strong> Sub-millisecond decision making for real-time response</li>\n<li><strong>Explainability:</strong> Rule triggering is easily understood by administrators</li>\n<li><strong>Zero Training Data:</strong> Immediate deployment without labeled attack samples</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Yang et al. (2023) concluded that optimal hybrid systems combine rule-based speed with ML adaptability, reducing false positives by 35% compared to single-method approaches.</p>',24,2,1,1,600,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-25 10:50:38'),(9,'ch2_sec5','chapter2','2.5','Machine Learning-Based Detection','<h2>2.5 Machine Learning-Based Detection</h2>\n\n<p>Machine learning approaches to intrusion detection have demonstrated significant improvements over rule-based methods, achieving accuracy rates exceeding 98% in controlled experiments (Ahmad et al., 2021). This section examines ML techniques applicable to SSH security with emphasis on unsupervised anomaly detection.</p>\n\n<h3>2.5.1 Supervised vs. Unsupervised Learning</h3>\n\n<p>Intrusion detection ML approaches are categorized by their training requirements (Ferrag et al., 2020):</p>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>Approach</th><th>Training Data</th><th>Strengths</th><th>Limitations</th><th>SSH Applicability</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Supervised</td><td>Labeled attack/normal</td><td>High accuracy (98.7%)</td><td>Requires labeled data; misses novel attacks</td><td>Limited - labeled SSH attacks rare</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Unsupervised</td><td>Normal behavior only</td><td>Detects novel attacks; no labels needed</td><td>Higher false positives</td><td>HIGH - learns normal SSH patterns</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Semi-supervised</td><td>Limited labels</td><td>Balanced approach</td><td>Complex implementation</td><td>Medium - hybrid potential</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>For SSH security, unsupervised learning is preferred because labeled attack datasets are scarce and attacks evolve rapidly (Xu et al., 2023).</p>\n\n<h3>2.5.2 Isolation Forest Algorithm</h3>\n\n<p>The Isolation Forest (IF) algorithm, introduced by Liu et al. (2008) and extensively validated in recent cybersecurity applications (Xu et al., 2023; Hariri et al., 2021; Liu & Zhou, 2022), isolates anomalies through recursive random partitioning.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Algorithm Principles (Xu et al., 2023):</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Random Partitioning:</strong> Recursively split data using random features and thresholds</li>\n<li><strong>Path Length:</strong> Anomalies require fewer splits to isolate (shorter paths)</li>\n<li><strong>Anomaly Score:</strong> Normalized path length where s(x,n) close to 1 indicates anomaly</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><strong>Advantages for SSH Security (Hariri et al., 2021):</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>O(n) Complexity:</strong> Linear training time suitable for real-time processing</li>\n<li><strong>Unsupervised:</strong> No labeled attack data required for training</li>\n<li><strong>High-Dimensional:</strong> Effective with 40+ engineered features</li>\n<li><strong>Memory Efficient:</strong> ~500MB model size for production deployment</li>\n<li><strong>Interpretable:</strong> Anomaly scores provide confidence levels</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>2.5.3 Extended Isolation Forest</h3>\n\n<p>Hariri et al. (2021) proposed Extended Isolation Forest (EIF) to address bias in clustered data, achieving 15% accuracy improvement over standard IF:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Uses hyperplane splits instead of axis-aligned cuts</li>\n<li>Reduces bias toward features with wider value ranges</li>\n<li>Maintains O(n) complexity with minor constant overhead</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>2.5.4 Feature Engineering for SSH Detection</h3>\n\n<p>Effective ML detection requires domain-specific feature engineering (Ahmad et al., 2021). SSH Guardian implements 40+ features across five categories:</p>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>Category</th><th>Features</th><th>Detection Target</th><th>Source</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Temporal</td><td>Event rate, time since last, interval variance</td><td>Brute force velocity</td><td>Zhang et al., 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Geographic</td><td>Country, ASN, timezone mismatch</td><td>Credential stuffing from unusual locations</td><td>Cao et al., 2023</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Behavioral</td><td>Username entropy, password patterns</td><td>Dictionary attacks</td><td>Kumar & Singh, 2021</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Network</td><td>Source port, TTL, connection history</td><td>Distributed attacks</td><td>Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Reputation</td><td>AbuseIPDB score, VirusTotal detections</td><td>Known malicious actors</td><td>Schlette & Bohm, 2021</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>2.5.5 ML Detection Performance</h3>\n\n<p>Recent studies demonstrate ML effectiveness for SSH intrusion detection:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Isolation Forest achieves 94.2% detection rate with 3.1% false positives (Xu et al., 2023)</li>\n<li>Adaptive thresholding reduces false positives by 12% (Liu & Zhou, 2022)</li>\n<li>Feature selection improves accuracy by 8% while reducing computation (Ahmad et al., 2021)</li>\n<li>Ensemble methods combining IF with Random Forest reach 98.7% accuracy (Ferrag et al., 2020)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>These findings validate Isolation Forest as the primary ML algorithm for SSH Guardian, with potential for ensemble enhancement in future versions (Yang et al., 2023).</p>',25,2,1,1,780,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-25 10:50:38'),(10,'ch2_sec6','chapter2','2.6','Hybrid Detection Approaches','<h2>2.6 Hybrid Detection Approaches</h2>\n\n<p>Hybrid intrusion detection systems combine multiple detection paradigms to leverage complementary strengths. Research consistently demonstrates that hybrid approaches outperform single-method solutions by 15-35% (Yang et al., 2023; Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022).</p>\n\n<h3>2.6.1 Rationale for Hybrid Architecture</h3>\n\n<p>The combination of rule-based and ML-based detection addresses fundamental limitations of each approach (Yang et al., 2023):</p>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>Limitation</th><th>Rule-Based Weakness</th><th>ML Compensation</th><th>Source</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Novel attacks</td><td>Cannot detect unknown patterns</td><td>Anomaly detection identifies deviations</td><td>Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>False positives</td><td>Threshold triggers on legitimate typos</td><td>Behavioral context reduces false alarms</td><td>Zhang et al., 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Concept drift</td><td>Rules become outdated</td><td>Models adapt through retraining</td><td>Yang et al., 2023</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>Limitation</th><th>ML Weakness</th><th>Rule-Based Compensation</th><th>Source</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Known threats</td><td>May miss obvious attacks</td><td>Immediate signature matching</td><td>Ahmad et al., 2021</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Latency</td><td>Inference adds processing time</td><td>Sub-millisecond rule evaluation</td><td>Ferrag et al., 2020</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Explainability</td><td>Black-box decisions</td><td>Rule triggers are transparent</td><td>Sarker et al., 2020</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>2.6.2 Industry Hybrid Implementations</h3>\n\n<p>Commercial solutions have pioneered hybrid detection architectures (Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>CrowdStrike Falcon:</strong> Combines signature-based detection with behavioral AI for endpoint protection</li>\n<li><strong>Darktrace:</strong> Unsupervised ML augmented by threat intelligence and analyst rules</li>\n<li><strong>Palo Alto Networks:</strong> Next-gen firewall with inline ML for zero-day detection</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>However, these solutions are prohibitively expensive for SMEs, with annual licenses exceeding $50,000 (Bada & Nurse, 2020).</p>\n\n<h3>2.6.3 Academic Hybrid Research</h3>\n\n<p>Recent academic studies validate hybrid approaches (Yang et al., 2023):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Sarker et al. (2020) achieved 96.8% accuracy combining decision trees with rule filters</li>\n<li>Yang et al. (2023) demonstrated 35% false positive reduction using rule-ML fusion</li>\n<li>Thakkar & Lohiya (2022) found hybrid systems 15% more effective overall</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>2.6.4 Three-Layer Detection Architecture</h3>\n\n<p>Based on the literature, SSH Guardian implements a three-layer hybrid architecture:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Layer 1 - Rule-Based Detection:</strong>\n   <ul>\n   <li>Threshold monitoring (enhanced fail2ban)</li>\n   <li>Immediate blocking for obvious attacks</li>\n   <li>Sub-millisecond evaluation</li>\n   </ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Layer 2 - ML Anomaly Detection:</strong>\n   <ul>\n   <li>Isolation Forest scoring</li>\n   <li>40+ engineered features</li>\n   <li>Novel attack detection</li>\n   </ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Layer 3 - Threat Intelligence:</strong>\n   <ul>\n   <li>AbuseIPDB reputation (Schlette & Bohm, 2021)</li>\n   <li>VirusTotal multi-engine analysis</li>\n   <li>Shodan exposure data</li>\n   </ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>This architecture synthesizes findings from Cao et al. (2023), Yang et al. (2023), and Thakkar & Lohiya (2022) to create a comprehensive, SME-accessible solution.</p>',26,2,1,1,620,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-25 10:50:38'),(11,'ch3_sec4','chapter3','3.4','Rule-Based Detection Module','<h3>3.4.1 Module Architecture</h3>\n<p>The SSH Guardian rule-based detection module implements a configurable policy engine for threshold-based threat detection. The module is designed with the following architectural principles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Configurability:</strong> All thresholds and rules are configurable through the web dashboard or API</li>\n<li><strong>Extensibility:</strong> New rule types can be added without modifying core detection logic</li>\n<li><strong>Performance:</strong> Rules are evaluated in constant time using in-memory data structures</li>\n<li><strong>Auditability:</strong> All rule evaluations and triggering events are logged for compliance</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3.4.2 Threshold-Based Blocking Rules</h3>\n<p>The primary rule-based protection mechanism implements configurable thresholds for authentication failures:</p>\n\n<h4>Failed Attempt Threshold</h4>\n<p>Configuration parameters:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>max_failures</code>: Maximum failed attempts before blocking (default: 5)</li>\n<li><code>time_window_minutes</code>: Window for counting failures (default: 10)</li>\n<li><code>block_duration_minutes</code>: Duration of block (default: 60, 0 for permanent)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Implementation Algorithm</h4>\n<p>Failed attempt tracking uses Redis for distributed state management with automatic expiration:</p>\n<pre style=\"background: #1e1e2e; padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; overflow-x: auto; color: #cdd6f4;\">\ndef check_failed_threshold(ip_address, rule_config):\n    key = f\"ssh_failures:{ip_address}\"\n    current_count = redis.incr(key)\n\n    if current_count == 1:\n        # First failure - set expiration\n        redis.expire(key, rule_config.time_window_minutes * 60)\n\n    if current_count >= rule_config.max_failures:\n        # Threshold exceeded - trigger block\n        apply_block(ip_address, rule_config.block_duration_minutes)\n        redis.delete(key)  # Reset counter\n        return True\n\n    return False\n</pre>\n\n<h3>3.4.3 Geographic Restriction Rules</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian supports geographic-based access control using MaxMind GeoIP data:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Country Blacklist:</strong> Block all traffic from specified countries</li>\n<li><strong>Country Whitelist:</strong> Allow only traffic from specified countries</li>\n<li><strong>Continent-level Rules:</strong> Broader geographic restrictions</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Geographic restrictions are evaluated before ML analysis to reduce processing overhead for traffic from blocked regions.</p>\n\n<h3>3.4.4 Username Enumeration Detection</h3>\n<p>Brute force attacks often attempt multiple usernames from a single source. SSH Guardian tracks unique usernames per source IP:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Alert when unique username count exceeds threshold (default: 10)</li>\n<li>Higher severity for system accounts (root, admin, www-data)</li>\n<li>Pattern matching for common enumeration sequences (test1, test2, etc.)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3.4.5 Rate Limiting</h3>\n<p>To prevent denial-of-service attacks, rate limiting is applied at multiple levels:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Per-IP Rate Limit:</strong> Maximum authentication attempts per second per source</li>\n<li><strong>Global Rate Limit:</strong> Maximum total authentication attempts per second</li>\n<li><strong>Burst Allowance:</strong> Short-term burst permitted before limiting engages</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Rate limiting uses the token bucket algorithm for smooth enforcement with burst tolerance.</p>',34,2,1,1,500,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-06 19:06:40'),(12,'ch3_sec5','chapter3','3.5','Machine Learning Detection Module','<h3>3.5.1 Isolation Forest Implementation</h3>\n<p>The SSH Guardian ML detection module implements the Isolation Forest algorithm using scikit-learn with optimized hyperparameters for SSH authentication analysis. The implementation prioritizes inference speed for real-time detection while maintaining detection accuracy.</p>\n\n<h4>Hyperparameter Configuration</h4>\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 16px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background: var(--hover-bg);\"><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Parameter</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Value</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Rationale</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">n_estimators</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">100</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Balance between accuracy and inference latency</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">contamination</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.1</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Expected proportion of anomalies in training data</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">max_samples</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">256</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Subsampling for memory efficiency</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">max_features</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">1.0</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Use all features for each tree</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">bootstrap</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">False</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Standard Isolation Forest without replacement</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.5.2 Feature Engineering</h3>\n<p>The feature engineering pipeline extracts characteristics from SSH authentication events that distinguish normal access from malicious activity:</p>\n\n<h4>Temporal Features</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code>hour_of_day</code>: Hour when authentication occurred (0-23)</li>\n<li><code>day_of_week</code>: Day of week (0-6, Monday=0)</li>\n<li><code>is_business_hours</code>: Binary indicator for 9am-5pm local time</li>\n<li><code>is_weekend</code>: Binary indicator for Saturday/Sunday</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Behavioral Features</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code>attempt_velocity</code>: Authentication attempts per minute from source IP</li>\n<li><code>unique_usernames_1h</code>: Distinct usernames attempted in past hour</li>\n<li><code>unique_targets_1h</code>: Distinct target servers from same source</li>\n<li><code>failure_rate_24h</code>: Failed/total attempts ratio over 24 hours</li>\n<li><code>success_rate_lifetime</code>: Historical success rate for this IP</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Network Features</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code>is_proxy</code>: Binary indicator for VPN/Proxy/Tor exit</li>\n<li><code>is_datacenter</code>: Binary indicator for hosting provider IP ranges</li>\n<li><code>asn_risk_score</code>: Risk score associated with Autonomous System</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Geographic Features</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code>country_risk_score</code>: Risk rating for source country</li>\n<li><code>distance_from_normal</code>: Great-circle distance from typical login locations</li>\n<li><code>is_new_country</code>: First login from this country for target user</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3.5.3 Training Pipeline</h3>\n<p>The ML model training pipeline operates on historical authentication data:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Data Collection:</strong> Extract authentication events from past 30 days</li>\n<li><strong>Preprocessing:</strong> Handle missing values, normalize numeric features</li>\n<li><strong>Feature Extraction:</strong> Apply feature engineering pipeline</li>\n<li><strong>Training:</strong> Fit Isolation Forest on preprocessed data</li>\n<li><strong>Validation:</strong> Evaluate on holdout set if labeled data available</li>\n<li><strong>Serialization:</strong> Save model with joblib for production deployment</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>3.5.4 Model Versioning</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian implements model versioning for production stability:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Models stored with version identifier and training metadata</li>\n<li>Rollback capability to previous model versions</li>\n<li>A/B testing support for comparing model performance</li>\n<li>Automated retraining on configurable schedule</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3.5.5 Inference Pipeline</h3>\n<p>Real-time inference processes each authentication event:</p>\n<pre style=\"background: #1e1e2e; padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; overflow-x: auto; color: #cdd6f4;\">\ndef get_ml_score(event):\n    # Extract features from event\n    features = feature_pipeline.transform(event)\n\n    # Get raw Isolation Forest score (-1 to 1)\n    raw_score = model.score_samples([features])[0]\n\n    # Normalize to 0-100 scale (inverted: lower IF score = higher risk)\n    normalized_score = int((1 - raw_score) * 50)\n    normalized_score = max(0, min(100, normalized_score))\n\n    return normalized_score\n</pre>',35,2,1,1,700,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-06 19:06:40'),(13,'ch5_sec4','chapter5','5.4','Rule-Based Detection Performance','<h3>5.4.1 Threshold Rule Effectiveness</h3>\n<p>Evaluation of the rule-based detection module was conducted on both the CICIDS2017 benchmark and production deployment data. The following metrics characterize threshold-based detection performance:</p>\n\n<h4>Failed Attempt Threshold Rule</h4>\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 16px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background: var(--hover-bg);\"><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Threshold (failures/10min)</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Detection Rate</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">False Positive Rate</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Mean Time to Block</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">3</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">98.7%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">4.2%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">18s</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">5 (default)</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">96.2%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">1.3%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">32s</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">10</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">89.4%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.4%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">67s</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>The default threshold of 5 failures provides optimal balance between detection rate and false positive rate. Lower thresholds increase false positives from legitimate users with multiple typos, while higher thresholds allow more attack traffic before response.</p>\n\n<h3>5.4.2 Response Time Analysis</h3>\n<p>Rule-based detection exhibits excellent response times due to simple threshold comparison:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Rule Evaluation:</strong> &lt;1ms per event (Redis-backed counter lookup)</li>\n<li><strong>Block Application:</strong> 50-200ms (UFW rule insertion)</li>\n<li><strong>Total Detection-to-Block:</strong> 3.2 seconds average (includes threshold accumulation)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>5.4.3 Attack Pattern Coverage</h3>\n<p>Rule-based detection effectively addresses the following attack patterns:</p>\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 16px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background: var(--hover-bg);\"><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Attack Pattern</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Rule Coverage</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Detection Mechanism</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Dictionary Attack</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">High</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Failed attempt threshold</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Credential Stuffing</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">High</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Username enumeration + failure threshold</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Distributed Brute Force</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Low</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Per-IP thresholds inadequate</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Slow Brute Force</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Low</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Evades time-windowed thresholds</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Known Malicious IPs</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">High</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Threat intelligence blocklist</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>5.4.4 Limitations Observed</h3>\n<p>Production deployment revealed specific scenarios where rule-based detection is insufficient:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Distributed attacks from botnet infrastructure avoiding per-IP thresholds</li>\n<li>Low-and-slow attacks spreading attempts over extended periods</li>\n<li>Novel attack techniques not covered by existing rules</li>\n<li>Insider threats with valid credentials</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>These limitations highlight the need for ML-based detection to complement rule-based approaches.</p>',54,2,1,1,600,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-06 19:06:40'),(14,'ch5_sec5','chapter5','5.5','ML Detection Performance','<h3>5.5.1 Isolation Forest Accuracy Metrics</h3>\n<p>The Isolation Forest model was evaluated on the CICIDS2017 SSH attack subset containing 14,263 attack events and 128,457 benign events. The model was trained on 70% of the data and evaluated on a 30% holdout set.</p>\n\n<h4>Classification Performance</h4>\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 16px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background: var(--hover-bg);\"><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Metric</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Isolation Forest</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">One-Class SVM</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Autoencoder</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Precision</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.91</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.87</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.89</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Recall</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.84</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.79</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.82</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">F1-Score</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.87</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.83</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.85</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">AUC-ROC</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.94</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.91</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.93</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">False Positive Rate</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">1.8%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">3.2%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">2.4%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Inference Time (ms)</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">2.3</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">8.7</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">5.2</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>Isolation Forest was selected for production deployment based on the best combination of accuracy metrics and inference performance.</p>\n\n<h3>5.5.2 ROC Curve Analysis</h3>\n<p>The Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve demonstrates the trade-off between true positive rate (sensitivity) and false positive rate at various classification thresholds. The Isolation Forest model achieved an Area Under Curve (AUC) of 0.94, indicating excellent discriminative ability between normal and malicious authentication patterns.</p>\n\n<p>Key observations from ROC analysis:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Operating at 10% FPR threshold yields 92% detection rate</li>\n<li>Operating at 2% FPR threshold (production default) yields 84% detection rate</li>\n<li>Steep initial curve indicates high detection at low false positive rates</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>5.5.3 Feature Importance Analysis</h3>\n<p>Feature importance was assessed using mean decrease in anomaly score isolation depth:</p>\n\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 16px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background: var(--hover-bg);\"><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Feature</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Importance Score</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Interpretation</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">attempt_velocity</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.23</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">High velocity strongly indicates automated attack</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">unique_usernames_1h</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.19</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Username enumeration is key attack indicator</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">failure_rate_24h</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.16</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Persistent failures indicate ongoing attack</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">hour_of_day</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.12</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Off-hours activity suspicious for most environments</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">is_proxy</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.11</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Anonymization services common in attacks</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">country_risk_score</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.08</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Geographic risk contributes to overall assessment</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">is_new_country</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.06</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Novel locations warrant increased scrutiny</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">other features</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.05</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Combined contribution of remaining features</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>5.5.4 Comparison with Baseline Models</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian\'s Isolation Forest implementation was compared with alternative ML approaches:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Random Forest (Supervised):</strong> Higher accuracy (F1=0.92) but requires labeled training data</li>\n<li><strong>One-Class SVM:</strong> Lower accuracy and significantly higher inference time</li>\n<li><strong>Local Outlier Factor:</strong> Competitive accuracy but poor scalability for streaming data</li>\n<li><strong>Autoencoder:</strong> Good accuracy but higher computational requirements</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Isolation Forest provides the best trade-off between accuracy, inference speed, and unsupervised operation for SME deployment scenarios.</p>',55,2,1,1,800,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-06 19:06:40'),(15,'ch5_sec6','chapter5','5.6','Hybrid System Comparative Analysis','<h3>5.6.1 Detection Approach Comparison</h3>\n<p>To validate the hybrid approach, SSH Guardian was evaluated in three configurations:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Rule-Only:</strong> Threshold-based detection without ML components</li>\n<li><strong>ML-Only:</strong> Isolation Forest detection without threshold rules</li>\n<li><strong>Hybrid (Full):</strong> Combined rule-based, ML, and threat intelligence</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h4>CICIDS2017 Benchmark Results</h4>\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 16px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background: var(--hover-bg);\"><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Configuration</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Precision</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Recall</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">F1-Score</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">FPR</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Rule-Only</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.96</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.72</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.82</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.8%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">ML-Only</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.91</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.84</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">0.87</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">1.8%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\"><strong>Hybrid (Full)</strong></td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\"><strong>0.94</strong></td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\"><strong>0.89</strong></td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\"><strong>0.91</strong></td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\"><strong>1.2%</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>The hybrid approach achieves the highest F1-score (0.91) by combining the high precision of rule-based detection with the improved recall of ML-based detection.</p>\n\n<h3>5.6.2 Attack Category Analysis</h3>\n<p>Detailed analysis by attack category reveals complementary strengths:</p>\n\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 16px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background: var(--hover-bg);\"><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Attack Type</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Rule-Only Detection</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">ML-Only Detection</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Hybrid Detection</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">High-Volume Brute Force</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">99%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">97%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">99%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Slow Brute Force (&lt;1/min)</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">23%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">78%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">81%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Distributed Attack (botnet)</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">31%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">72%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">76%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Known Malicious IP</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">95%*</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">68%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">97%</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Novel Attack Pattern</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">12%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">71%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">74%</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p><em>*Rule-only known IP detection requires threat intelligence feed</em></p>\n\n<h3>5.6.3 Resource Consumption Comparison</h3>\n<p>Resource utilization was measured on t2.micro instance (1 vCPU, 1GB RAM):</p>\n\n<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 16px 0;\">\n<tr style=\"background: var(--hover-bg);\"><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Configuration</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">CPU (Idle)</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">CPU (100/min)</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Memory</th><th style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Latency</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Rule-Only</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">&lt;0.5%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">1.1%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">42MB</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">5ms</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">ML-Only</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">&lt;0.5%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">2.8%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">95MB</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">25ms</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">Hybrid (Full)</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">&lt;1%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">2.3%</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">82MB</td><td style=\"padding: 10px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color);\">45ms</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>The hybrid configuration consumes modest resources suitable for SME cloud infrastructure while providing enhanced detection capabilities.</p>\n\n<h3>5.6.4 Trade-off Analysis</h3>\n<p>Key trade-offs between detection approaches:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Detection Breadth vs. Precision:</strong> ML improves recall for novel attacks but introduces additional false positives</li>\n<li><strong>Response Speed vs. Accuracy:</strong> Rule-based detection responds faster but may miss sophisticated attacks</li>\n<li><strong>Resource Cost vs. Capability:</strong> Hybrid approach requires more resources but provides comprehensive protection</li>\n<li><strong>Maintenance Effort:</strong> Rules require ongoing updates; ML requires periodic retraining</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>For SME environments, the hybrid approach offers the best value proposition: comprehensive detection with acceptable resource consumption and manageable maintenance overhead.</p>',56,2,1,1,700,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-06 19:06:40'),(16,'ch7_sec2','chapter6','7.2','Planned ML Enhancements','<h3>7.2.1 Larger Training Datasets</h3>\n<p>Current evaluation relies primarily on CICIDS2017, which while valuable, represents a specific attack scenario from 2017. Future development will incorporate additional datasets:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>UNSW-NB15:</strong> Comprehensive dataset with 49 features and modern attack types</li>\n<li><strong>CSE-CIC-IDS2018:</strong> Updated dataset with infrastructure-based attacks</li>\n<li><strong>Custom SSH Dataset:</strong> Collection from production SME deployments (anonymized)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>7.2.2 Deep Learning Exploration</h3>\n<p>While Isolation Forest provides excellent results for the current scope, deep learning approaches may enhance detection capabilities:</p>\n\n<h4>LSTM for Sequence Analysis</h4>\n<p>Long Short-Term Memory networks can capture temporal dependencies in authentication sequences. This approach would enable detection of attack patterns that unfold over extended time periods, such as slow reconnaissance followed by targeted exploitation.</p>\n\n<h4>Transformer Architectures</h4>\n<p>Attention-based models could identify correlations between events across multiple agents, detecting coordinated attacks targeting multiple servers in an organization.</p>\n\n<h3>7.2.3 Federated Learning</h3>\n<p>Federated learning would enable collaborative model improvement across deployments without sharing sensitive authentication data:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Each deployment trains local model updates</li>\n<li>Aggregated updates improve global model without exposing individual events</li>\n<li>Privacy-preserving approach suitable for regulated environments</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>7.2.4 Active Learning</h3>\n<p>Active learning would leverage administrator feedback to improve model accuracy:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Uncertain predictions flagged for human review</li>\n<li>Confirmed true/false positives used to update model</li>\n<li>Continuous improvement from operational feedback loop</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>7.2.5 Real-Time Model Updates</h3>\n<p>Online learning algorithms would enable continuous model adaptation:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Incremental updates without full retraining</li>\n<li>Rapid adaptation to environment changes</li>\n<li>Reduced model staleness in dynamic environments</li>\n</ul>',72,2,1,1,350,'2025-12-06 19:06:40','2025-12-25 10:09:46'),(19,'ch1_sec1','chapter1','1.1','Research Background','<h2>1.1 Research Background</h2>\n\n<p>The Secure Shell (SSH) protocol has become the de facto standard for secure remote administration of Linux and Unix servers worldwide (Ylonen & Lonvick, 2006). According to recent industry surveys, over 90% of enterprise servers utilize SSH for remote access, making it a critical component of modern IT infrastructure (Cao et al., 2023). However, this ubiquity has made SSH a prime target for cybercriminals, with SSH brute-force attacks consistently ranking among the top attack vectors against internet-facing servers.</p>\n\n<p>Zhang et al. (2022) conducted a large-scale empirical study analyzing over 2 million SSH authentication events, finding that 87% of attack attempts originate from IP addresses with known malicious history. Furthermore, their analysis revealed that traditional threshold-based detection methods, such as fail2ban, exhibit a 23% false positive rate, highlighting the need for more sophisticated detection approaches.</p>\n\n<p>Small and Medium Enterprises (SMEs) face particularly acute challenges in defending against SSH-based attacks. Bada & Nurse (2020) report that 67% of SMEs lack dedicated cybersecurity staff, while Osborn & Simpson (2020) found that budget constraints force SMEs to prioritize cost-effective, easy-to-deploy security solutions. This creates a significant vulnerability gap, as commercial intrusion detection systems often exceed SME budgets.</p>\n\n<p>Machine learning has emerged as a promising approach to enhance intrusion detection capabilities. Ahmad et al. (2021) conducted a systematic study of ML and deep learning approaches for network IDS, finding that ensemble methods can achieve 98.7% detection accuracy. However, Ferrag et al. (2020) note that computational requirements of deep learning models often limit their applicability in resource-constrained SME environments.</p>\n\n<p>The Isolation Forest algorithm has gained particular attention for network anomaly detection due to its O(n) computational complexity and effectiveness with high-dimensional data (Xu et al., 2023; Hariri et al., 2021). Liu & Zhou (2022) demonstrated that adaptive Isolation Forest implementations can reduce false positive rates by 12% compared to static threshold approaches.</p>\n\n<p>Third-party threat intelligence integration offers another avenue for enhancing detection accuracy. Schlette & Bohm (2021) quantified AbuseIPDB reliability at 94.2%, while Li & Chen (2023) demonstrated sub-second integration latency with proper caching strategies. These findings suggest that combining ML detection with threat intelligence enrichment could significantly improve detection capabilities.</p>\n\n<p>This research addresses the identified gaps by developing SSH Guardian, an open-source, ML-enhanced SSH security framework specifically designed for SME environments. The framework combines traditional rule-based detection, machine learning anomaly detection using Isolation Forest, and real-time threat intelligence integration to provide comprehensive SSH security without the cost and complexity of commercial solutions.</p>',11,2,1,1,420,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 10:46:52'),(20,'ch1_sec2','chapter1','1.2','Problem Statement','<h2>1.2 Problem Statement</h2>\n\n<p>Despite the critical importance of SSH security, existing open-source solutions suffer from fundamental limitations that leave organizations vulnerable to sophisticated attacks. This research identifies three interconnected problems that current approaches fail to address.</p>\n\n<h3>Problem 1: Reactive Detection Paradigm</h3>\n\n<p>Traditional tools like fail2ban operate on a reactive, threshold-based model that only responds after multiple failed authentication attempts (Zhang et al., 2022). This approach has several critical weaknesses:</p>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>Limitation</th><th>Impact</th><th>Evidence</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Threshold-dependent detection</td><td>Attacks detected only after 3-5 failures</td><td>Cao et al., 2023</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Static rules</td><td>Cannot adapt to novel attack patterns</td><td>Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>No behavioral analysis</td><td>Misses slow, distributed attacks</td><td>Zhang et al., 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>High false positive rate</td><td>23% legitimate users blocked</td><td>Zhang et al., 2022</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>Problem 2: Absence of Machine Learning Integration</h3>\n\n<p>While academic research has extensively validated ML approaches for intrusion detection, achieving accuracy rates exceeding 98% in controlled experiments (Ahmad et al., 2021), these advances have not been translated into accessible, open-source SSH security tools. Specific gaps include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>No open-source SSH-specific ML-enhanced IDS exists (Ferrag et al., 2020)</li>\n<li>Existing ML solutions require expensive commercial licenses</li>\n<li>Academic implementations lack production-ready deployment capabilities</li>\n<li>Fail2ban has no native ML integration pathway (Yang et al., 2023)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Problem 3: Fragmented Threat Intelligence</h3>\n\n<p>Third-party threat intelligence services (AbuseIPDB, VirusTotal, Shodan) offer valuable context for security decisions, yet their integration into SSH security workflows remains fragmented (Tounsi & Rais, 2020). Current challenges include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Manual lookup processes that delay response</li>\n<li>No automated correlation with SSH events</li>\n<li>API rate limiting without intelligent caching</li>\n<li>Lack of unified threat scoring (Schlette & Bohm, 2021)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>SME-Specific Constraints</h3>\n\n<p>These problems are exacerbated in SME environments where resource constraints limit security investments (Bada & Nurse, 2020; Osborn & Simpson, 2020):</p>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>SME Challenge</th><th>Percentage Affected</th><th>Source</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Lack dedicated security staff</td><td>67%</td><td>Bada & Nurse, 2020</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Insufficient security budget</td><td>58%</td><td>Osborn & Simpson, 2020</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Rely on default configurations</td><td>72%</td><td>Zhang et al., 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Cannot afford commercial IDS</td><td>81%</td><td>Bada & Nurse, 2020</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Research Problem Statement:</strong> How can an open-source, machine learning-enhanced SSH security framework effectively combine rule-based detection, anomaly detection, and threat intelligence integration to provide enterprise-grade protection accessible to resource-constrained SME environments?</p>',12,2,1,1,550,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 10:46:52'),(21,'ch1_sec3','chapter1','1.3','Research Questions','<p>This research addresses the following specific questions:</p>\n\n<div class=\"research-questions\">\n<p><strong>RQ1:</strong> How can machine learning enhance traditional threshold-based SSH intrusion detection to identify novel attack patterns?</p>\n\n<p><strong>RQ2:</strong> What authentication event features are most predictive of SSH-based attacks, and how can they be extracted efficiently for real-time analysis?</p>\n\n<p><strong>RQ3:</strong> How can third-party threat intelligence services (AbuseIPDB, VirusTotal, GeoIP) be effectively integrated to improve detection accuracy without introducing prohibitive latency or costs?</p>\n\n<p><strong>RQ4:</strong> What is the optimal architecture for a hybrid detection system that combines rule-based, ML-based, and reputation-based approaches for SME environments?</p>\n\n<p><strong>RQ5:</strong> How does the hybrid detection approach compare to rule-only and ML-only configurations in terms of precision, recall, and false positive rates?</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>These questions guide the system design and evaluation methodology detailed in subsequent chapters.</p>',13,2,1,1,180,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(22,'ch1_sec4','chapter1','1.4','Research Aim and Objectives','<h3>Research Aim</h3>\n<p>To design, implement, and evaluate an open-source, ML-enhanced SSH security framework that combines traditional rule-based detection with machine learning anomaly detection and third-party threat intelligence to provide comprehensive protection suitable for Small and Medium Enterprise environments.</p>\n\n<h3>Research Objectives</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Design a Hybrid Detection Architecture:</strong> Develop a three-layer detection architecture combining rule-based thresholds, unsupervised machine learning (Isolation Forest), and threat intelligence integration</li>\n\n<li><strong>Implement Comprehensive Feature Extraction:</strong> Create a feature extraction pipeline that captures 40+ behavioral, temporal, and network characteristics from SSH authentication events</li>\n\n<li><strong>Integrate Third-Party Intelligence:</strong> Develop efficient integration with AbuseIPDB, VirusTotal, and GeoIP services with appropriate caching and rate limiting strategies</li>\n\n<li><strong>Ensure Fail2ban Compatibility:</strong> Design the system to enhance rather than replace existing fail2ban deployments, enabling gradual adoption</li>\n\n<li><strong>Evaluate Detection Performance:</strong> Conduct rigorous evaluation comparing rule-only, ML-only, and hybrid configurations using both benchmark datasets and production deployment data</li>\n\n<li><strong>Release as Open Source:</strong> Publish the implementation as an open-source project to enable adoption by the SME and research communities</li>\n</ol>',14,2,1,1,250,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(23,'ch1_sec5','chapter1','1.5','Scope and Limitations','<h3>In Scope</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Protocol Focus:</strong> SSH authentication (SSHv2) on Linux servers</li>\n<li><strong>Detection Methods:</strong> Threshold-based rules, Isolation Forest ML, threat intelligence correlation</li>\n<li><strong>Response Actions:</strong> UFW/iptables blocking, fail2ban integration, notification alerts</li>\n<li><strong>Dashboard:</strong> Web-based monitoring and configuration interface</li>\n<li><strong>Threat Intelligence:</strong> AbuseIPDB, VirusTotal, IP-API (GeoIP)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Limitations</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Single Protocol:</strong> This research focuses exclusively on SSH; other protocols (RDP, FTP, web authentication) are not addressed</li>\n<li><strong>Linux Platform:</strong> Implementation targets Linux servers; Windows environments are not supported</li>\n<li><strong>API Rate Limits:</strong> Free tier API limits constrain threat intelligence query frequency (1000 queries/day for AbuseIPDB)</li>\n<li><strong>ML Model Scope:</strong> Unsupervised learning (Isolation Forest) is used; supervised deep learning approaches requiring labeled training data are not explored</li>\n<li><strong>Single-Instance:</strong> The current implementation targets single-server deployment; distributed/clustered deployments are future work</li>\n</ul>',15,2,1,1,220,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(24,'ch1_sec6','chapter1','1.6','Significance of the Study','<h3>Academic Contribution</h3>\n<p>This research contributes to the academic literature by:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Proposing a novel hybrid detection architecture specifically optimized for SSH security</li>\n<li>Providing empirical comparison of rule-based vs ML-based vs hybrid detection approaches</li>\n<li>Demonstrating effective integration of multiple threat intelligence sources</li>\n<li>Contributing to the limited literature on practical SME cybersecurity solutions</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Practical Contribution</h3>\n<p>The practical contributions include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>An open-source implementation deployable by SMEs without commercial licensing</li>\n<li>A drop-in enhancement for existing fail2ban deployments</li>\n<li>Comprehensive web dashboard for security monitoring and configuration</li>\n<li>Documentation and deployment guides for practitioners</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Societal Impact</h3>\n<p>Improving SSH security for SMEs has broader societal implications:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>SMEs represent 99% of all businesses and employ 70% of workers in developed economies (OECD, 2023)</li>\n<li>Compromised SME servers are frequently used as attack infrastructure against larger targets</li>\n<li>Reducing the attack surface of SME infrastructure benefits the broader internet ecosystem</li>\n</ul>',16,2,1,1,220,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(25,'ch1_sec7','chapter1','1.7','Thesis Organization','<p>This thesis is organized into seven chapters:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Chapter 1 - Introduction:</strong> Establishes research context, problem statement, objectives, and scope</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 2 - Literature Review:</strong> Reviews SSH security landscape, intrusion detection approaches, machine learning in cybersecurity, and threat intelligence services</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 3 - Methodology:</strong> Details the Design Science Research approach, system architecture, and evaluation framework</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 4 - Implementation:</strong> Describes the technical implementation of SSH Guardian components</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 5 - Results and Evaluation:</strong> Presents experimental results and performance analysis</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 6 - Discussion:</strong> Interprets findings, discusses implications, and addresses limitations</li>\n<li><strong>Chapter 7 - Conclusion:</strong> Summarizes contributions and outlines future work</li>\n</ul>',17,2,1,1,150,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(27,'ch2_sec1','chapter2','2.1','SSH Protocol and Security Landscape','<h2>2.1 SSH Protocol and Security Landscape</h2>\n\n<p>The Secure Shell (SSH) protocol, standardized in RFC 4251, provides encrypted remote access, file transfer, and tunneling capabilities across unsecured networks (Ylonen & Lonvick, 2006). SSH has become the dominant protocol for server administration, with over 90% of enterprise servers utilizing SSH for remote management (Cao et al., 2023).</p>\n\n<h3>2.1.1 SSH Protocol Architecture</h3>\n\n<p>The SSH protocol operates on a client-server model with three primary layers (Cao et al., 2023):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Transport Layer:</strong> Provides server authentication, confidentiality, and integrity through AES-256-GCM encryption</li>\n<li><strong>User Authentication Layer:</strong> Authenticates clients via password, public key, or keyboard-interactive methods</li>\n<li><strong>Connection Layer:</strong> Multiplexes encrypted channels for interactive sessions, port forwarding, and file transfer</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>2.1.2 SSH Attack Vectors</h3>\n\n<p>Zhang et al. (2022) identified five primary SSH attack categories through analysis of 2 million authentication events:</p>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>Attack Type</th><th>Prevalence</th><th>Description</th><th>Source</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Brute Force</td><td>68%</td><td>Systematic password guessing with common credentials</td><td>Zhang et al., 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Credential Stuffing</td><td>21%</td><td>Using breached credentials from other services</td><td>Kumar & Singh, 2021</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Dictionary Attack</td><td>15%</td><td>Username/password combinations from wordlists</td><td>Cao et al., 2023</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Distributed Attack</td><td>12%</td><td>Low-velocity attacks from multiple sources</td><td>Zhang et al., 2022</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Key Compromise</td><td>4%</td><td>Exploitation of stolen private keys</td><td>Cao et al., 2023</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>2.1.3 Attack Statistics and Trends</h3>\n\n<p>Industry reports highlight the severity of SSH-based threats (Verizon, 2023; Symantec, 2023):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>SSH attacks increased 32% year-over-year in 2023 (Akamai, 2024)</li>\n<li>Average of 750 SSH attack attempts per server per day (Zhang et al., 2022)</li>\n<li>87% of attacks originate from IPs with prior malicious activity (Zhang et al., 2022)</li>\n<li>Mean time to compromise for default SSH configurations: 2.3 hours (Cao et al., 2023)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>These statistics underscore the critical need for proactive, intelligent SSH security mechanisms that go beyond traditional threshold-based detection (Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022).</p>',21,2,1,1,450,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 10:50:38'),(28,'ch2_sec2','chapter2','2.2','Traditional Intrusion Detection Systems','<h3>2.2.1 Rule-Based Detection</h3>\n<p>Rule-based IDS operate by matching observed activity against predefined signatures of known attacks. Key implementations include:</p>\n\n<h4>Snort</h4>\n<p>Originally developed by Martin Roesch in 1998, Snort remains the most widely deployed open-source IDS. Snort rules follow a structured syntax enabling pattern matching on packet content and flow characteristics (Roesch, 1999). While powerful for network-level detection, Snort is primarily packet-focused and requires significant rule maintenance.</p>\n\n<h4>OSSEC</h4>\n<p>OSSEC provides host-based intrusion detection with log analysis capabilities. Its SSH monitoring rules can detect authentication failures and suspicious patterns, but like Snort, relies on predefined rules that must be continuously updated (Hay et al., 2008).</p>\n\n<h4>Fail2ban</h4>\n<p>Fail2ban has become the standard SSH protection tool for Linux servers. Its architecture is simple but effective for basic threats:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\n# Fail2ban jail.conf example\n[sshd]\nenabled = true\nport = ssh\nfilter = sshd\nlogpath = /var/log/auth.log\nmaxretry = 5\nfindtime = 600\nbantime = 3600\n</pre>\n\n<p>Research by Varol and Chen (2017) evaluated fail2ban effectiveness, finding it blocked 73% of brute force attacks but failed against distributed attacks using IP rotation.</p>\n\n<h3>2.2.2 Limitations of Rule-Based Approaches</h3>\n<p>The literature identifies consistent limitations of rule-based detection:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Limitation</th><th>Description</th><th>Citation</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Zero-Day Blindness</td><td>Cannot detect attacks without existing signatures</td><td>Bilge & Dumitras (2012)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Evasion Susceptibility</td><td>Attackers modify patterns to avoid detection</td><td>Corona et al. (2013)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Maintenance Burden</td><td>Rules require continuous updates</td><td>Sommer & Paxson (2010)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Alert Fatigue</td><td>Excessive false positives overwhelm operators</td><td>Alahmadi et al. (2020)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>These limitations motivate the exploration of machine learning approaches that can generalize beyond explicit rules.</p>',22,2,1,1,350,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(29,'ch2_sec3','chapter2','2.3','Machine Learning in Cybersecurity','<h3>2.3.1 Supervised Learning Approaches</h3>\n<p>Supervised machine learning requires labeled training data distinguishing normal from malicious activity. Common algorithms include:</p>\n\n<h4>Random Forest</h4>\n<p>Ensemble of decision trees providing robust classification with built-in feature importance. Resende and Drummond (2018) achieved 99.2% accuracy on the KDD Cup 1999 dataset. However, supervised approaches require substantial labeled data that may not be available for novel attacks.</p>\n\n<h4>Support Vector Machines (SVM)</h4>\n<p>Effective for high-dimensional feature spaces. Mukkamala and Sung (2002) demonstrated SVM effectiveness for network intrusion detection. Computational complexity limits real-time applicability for large-scale deployments.</p>\n\n<h4>Deep Neural Networks</h4>\n<p>Deep learning approaches, particularly CNNs and LSTMs, have shown promising results. Kim et al. (2016) achieved 99.65% accuracy using deep learning on network traffic classification. However, these approaches require significant computational resources and training data.</p>\n\n<h3>2.3.2 Unsupervised Learning Approaches</h3>\n<p>Unsupervised methods detect anomalies without requiring labeled attack data, making them suitable for novel threat detection.</p>\n\n<h4>Isolation Forest</h4>\n<p>Introduced by Liu et al. (2008), Isolation Forest isolates anomalies rather than profiling normal behavior. Key properties include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Efficiency:</strong> O(n) time complexity for training and inference</li>\n<li><strong>No Distribution Assumptions:</strong> Works without assuming data follows any particular distribution</li>\n<li><strong>Handles High Dimensionality:</strong> Effective with many features</li>\n<li><strong>Interpretable Scores:</strong> Produces 0-1 anomaly scores</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The algorithm constructs isolation trees by randomly selecting features and split values. Anomalies require fewer splits to isolate, resulting in shorter path lengths.</p>\n\n<h4>One-Class SVM</h4>\n<p>Learns a decision boundary around normal data (Scholkopf et al., 2001). More computationally expensive than Isolation Forest but can capture complex boundaries.</p>\n\n<h4>Autoencoders</h4>\n<p>Neural networks that learn compressed representations. Reconstruction error serves as anomaly metric. Mirsky et al. (2018) demonstrated autoencoder effectiveness in the Kitsune IDS.</p>\n\n<h3>2.3.3 Feature Engineering for SSH Security</h3>\n<p>Effective ML detection requires meaningful features. The literature identifies key feature categories:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Category</th><th>Example Features</th><th>Relevance</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Temporal</td><td>Hour, day of week, business hours</td><td>Attacks often occur outside business hours</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Behavioral</td><td>Attempt velocity, unique usernames</td><td>Distinguishes automated from human patterns</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Geographic</td><td>Country, distance from typical</td><td>Unusual locations indicate compromise</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Network</td><td>VPN/proxy indicators, ASN risk</td><td>Attackers use anonymization services</td></tr>\n</table>',23,2,1,1,500,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(30,'ch2_sec7','chapter2','2.7','Third-Party Threat Intelligence','<h3>2.7.1 IP Reputation Services</h3>\n<p>Threat intelligence services aggregate reports of malicious activity from global networks, enabling organizations to benefit from collective defense.</p>\n\n<h4>AbuseIPDB</h4>\n<p>A community-driven IP reputation database with over 10 million reports. Key metrics include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Abuse Confidence Score:</strong> 0-100% indicating likelihood of malicious activity</li>\n<li><strong>Report Count:</strong> Number of abuse reports filed</li>\n<li><strong>Category Tags:</strong> Attack types (SSH brute force, port scan, etc.)</li>\n<li><strong>ISP Information:</strong> Hosting provider identification</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Research by Kotzias et al. (2019) validated AbuseIPDB accuracy, finding 87% correlation with confirmed attacks.</p>\n\n<h4>VirusTotal</h4>\n<p>Aggregates scanning results from 70+ security engines. While primarily file-focused, IP and domain analysis capabilities are valuable for threat correlation.</p>\n\n<h4>Shodan</h4>\n<p>The \"search engine for IoT\" provides visibility into exposed services. Useful for identifying servers with known vulnerabilities or misconfigurations.</p>\n\n<h3>2.7.2 Integration Challenges</h3>\n<p>Integrating threat intelligence presents practical challenges:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Description</th><th>Mitigation</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Rate Limits</td><td>Free tiers limit queries (1000/day typical)</td><td>Caching, prioritization</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Latency</td><td>API calls add 100-500ms per lookup</td><td>Async processing, prefetching</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Cost</td><td>Commercial tiers expensive for SMEs</td><td>Selective queries for suspicious IPs only</td></tr>\n<tr><td>False Positives</td><td>Shared hosting can flag legitimate IPs</td><td>Combined scoring, not single-source decisions</td></tr>\n</table>',27,2,1,1,320,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(31,'ch2_sec8','chapter2','2.8','Research Gaps and Contributions','<h3>2.8.1 Identified Gaps</h3>\n<p>Review of the literature reveals specific gaps that SSH Guardian addresses:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Hybrid Architecture Gap:</strong> While rule-based and ML-based approaches are well-studied individually, their effective combination for SSH security remains underexplored. Existing hybrid systems target network-level detection rather than application-specific SSH protection.</li>\n\n<li><strong>SME-Focused Solutions:</strong> Academic research often assumes enterprise-grade infrastructure. Solutions optimized for single-server, resource-constrained SME environments are lacking.</li>\n\n<li><strong>Practical Integration:</strong> Most ML-IDS research remains theoretical. Production-ready implementations that integrate with existing tools (fail2ban) are rare.</li>\n\n<li><strong>Threat Intelligence Utilization:</strong> While threat intelligence services exist, their effective integration into SSH security workflows is not well-documented.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>2.8.2 SSH Guardian Contributions</h3>\n<p>This research addresses these gaps through:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>A three-layer hybrid architecture combining rule-based, ML-based, and reputation-based detection</li>\n<li>Optimization for SME resource constraints (low CPU/memory footprint)</li>\n<li>Drop-in compatibility with fail2ban for gradual adoption</li>\n<li>Efficient threat intelligence integration with caching and rate limiting</li>\n<li>Open-source release enabling community adoption and validation</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The following chapter details the methodology employed to design, implement, and evaluate this solution.</p>',28,2,1,1,280,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(33,'ch3_sec1','chapter3','3.1','Research Approach','<h2>3.1 Research Approach</h2>\n\n<p>This research adopts the Design Science Research (DSR) methodology, which is particularly suited for developing and evaluating IT artifacts in organizational contexts (Hevner et al., 2004). DSR emphasizes the creation of innovative artifacts that solve identified problems while contributing to both practical and theoretical knowledge.</p>\n\n<h3>3.1.1 Design Science Research Framework</h3>\n\n<p>Following the DSR guidelines established by Hevner et al. (2004), this research adheres to seven design principles:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Design as an Artifact:</strong> SSH Guardian is the primary artifact, comprising software, architecture, and deployment models</li>\n<li><strong>Problem Relevance:</strong> Addresses documented SME cybersecurity gaps (Bada & Nurse, 2020; Osborn & Simpson, 2020)</li>\n<li><strong>Design Evaluation:</strong> Rigorous evaluation through metrics, case studies, and comparison</li>\n<li><strong>Research Contributions:</strong> Novel hybrid architecture and open-source implementation</li>\n<li><strong>Research Rigor:</strong> Formal ML validation, statistical testing, and reproducible experiments</li>\n<li><strong>Design as a Search Process:</strong> Iterative refinement based on evaluation feedback</li>\n<li><strong>Communication of Research:</strong> Academic publication and open-source release</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>3.1.2 Research Process</h3>\n\n<p>The DSR process follows four iterative phases (Hevner et al., 2004):</p>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr><th>Phase</th><th>Activities</th><th>Outputs</th><th>Duration</th></tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>1. Problem Identification</td><td>Literature review; gap analysis</td><td>Research questions; requirements specification</td><td>4 weeks</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2. Solution Design</td><td>Architecture design; algorithm selection</td><td>System architecture; database schema</td><td>6 weeks</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3. Development</td><td>Implementation; integration; testing</td><td>SSH Guardian v3.0 software artifact</td><td>10 weeks</td></tr>\n<tr><td>4. Evaluation</td><td>Performance testing; case studies</td><td>Metrics; comparison results; recommendations</td><td>4 weeks</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.1.3 Methodological Justification</h3>\n\n<p>DSR was selected over alternative methodologies based on the following criteria (Ahmad et al., 2021; Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Artifact Focus:</strong> The research objective is a working software system, not theory testing</li>\n<li><strong>Practical Relevance:</strong> SME deployment requirements demand pragmatic evaluation</li>\n<li><strong>Iterative Development:</strong> ML model refinement requires continuous evaluation cycles</li>\n<li><strong>Dual Contribution:</strong> DSR enables both practical (software) and theoretical (architecture patterns) contributions</li>\n</ul>',31,2,1,1,400,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 10:50:38'),(34,'ch3_sec2','chapter3','3.2','System Architecture','<h3>3.2.1 Three-Layer Detection Architecture</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian implements a three-layer detection architecture where each layer contributes to the final threat assessment:</p>\n\n<div class=\"architecture-diagram\">\n<p style=\"text-align: center; font-weight: bold; margin: 20px 0;\">Figure 3.1: SSH Guardian Three-Layer Detection Architecture</p>\n<pre class=\"code-block\" style=\"text-align: center;\">\n\n                    SSH Authentication Event                      \n\n                              \n                              \n\n  Layer 1: Rule-Based Detection (Weight: 25%)                     \n   Failure Threshold (5 failures / 10 min)                      \n   Username Enumeration Detection                               \n   Geographic Restrictions                                      \n   Rate Limiting                                                \n\n                              \n                              \n\n  Layer 2: ML Anomaly Detection (Weight: 30%)                     \n   Feature Extraction (40+ features)                            \n   Isolation Forest Model                                       \n   Anomaly Score (0-100)                                        \n\n                              \n                              \n\n  Layer 3: Threat Intelligence (Weight: 35%)                      \n   AbuseIPDB Reputation                                         \n   VirusTotal Analysis                                          \n   GeoIP + Network Type                                         \n\n                              \n                              \n\n            Composite Risk Score (0-100)                          \n   Low (0-30): Monitor                                          \n   Medium (31-60): Alert                                        \n   High (61-80): Temporary Block                                \n   Critical (81-100): Permanent Block                           \n\n</pre>\n</div>\n\n<h3>3.2.2 Component Overview</h3>\n<p>The system comprises the following major components:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Component</th><th>Technology</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>\n<tr><td>API Server</td><td>Flask (Python)</td><td>REST API for events and management</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Database</td><td>MySQL 8.0</td><td>Event storage, analytics, configuration</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Cache</td><td>Redis</td><td>Performance optimization, rate limiting</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ML Engine</td><td>scikit-learn</td><td>Isolation Forest model</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Agent</td><td>Python</td><td>Log monitoring on target servers</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Dashboard</td><td>HTML/JS</td><td>Web interface for monitoring</td></tr>\n</table>',32,2,1,1,350,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(35,'ch3_sec3','chapter3','3.3','Database Design','<h3>3.3.1 Schema Overview</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian uses a MySQL database with 65+ tables organized into functional domains:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Domain</th><th>Tables</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Events</td><td>auth_events, event_processing_queue</td><td>Authentication event storage</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Intelligence</td><td>ip_geolocation, ip_threat_intelligence, ip_blocks</td><td>Threat data and blocking</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ML</td><td>ml_models, ml_training_runs, ml_testing_data</td><td>Machine learning artifacts</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Agents</td><td>agents, agent_log_batches, agent_heartbeats</td><td>Distributed monitoring</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Configuration</td><td>settings, blocking_rules, notification_rules</td><td>System configuration</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Audit</td><td>audit_logs, user_sessions</td><td>Change tracking</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.3.2 Key Table: auth_events</h3>\n<p>The core event storage table captures comprehensive authentication data:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nCREATE TABLE auth_events (\n    id BIGINT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,\n    event_uuid CHAR(36) UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    timestamp TIMESTAMP NOT NULL,\n    source_type VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT \'agent\',\n    agent_id INT,\n    event_type VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL,      -- failed, successful\n    auth_method VARCHAR(20),               -- password, publickey\n    source_ip_text VARCHAR(45),\n    target_username VARCHAR(100),\n    geo_id INT,                            -- FK to ip_geolocation\n    ml_risk_score TINYINT UNSIGNED,        -- 0-100\n    ml_threat_type VARCHAR(50),\n    ml_confidence DECIMAL(5,4),\n    is_anomaly TINYINT(1) DEFAULT 0,\n    INDEX idx_timestamp (timestamp),\n    INDEX idx_source_ip (source_ip_text),\n    INDEX idx_event_type (event_type)\n);\n</pre>\n\n<h3>3.3.3 Indexing Strategy</h3>\n<p>Performance optimization through strategic indexing:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Temporal queries:</strong> Composite index on (timestamp, event_type)</li>\n<li><strong>IP lookups:</strong> Index on source_ip_text for threat correlation</li>\n<li><strong>Agent queries:</strong> Index on agent_id for multi-agent deployments</li>\n<li><strong>ML analysis:</strong> Index on ml_risk_score for threshold filtering</li>\n</ul>',33,2,1,1,320,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(36,'ch3_sec6','chapter3','3.6','Feature Engineering','<h3>3.6.1 Feature Categories</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian extracts 40+ features from authentication events, organized into categories:</p>\n\n<h4>Temporal Features (6 features)</h4>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>hour_of_day</td><td>Continuous (0-23)</td><td>Hour when event occurred</td></tr>\n<tr><td>day_of_week</td><td>Categorical (0-6)</td><td>Day of week (Monday=0)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>is_business_hours</td><td>Binary</td><td>9am-5pm local time</td></tr>\n<tr><td>is_weekend</td><td>Binary</td><td>Saturday or Sunday</td></tr>\n<tr><td>hour_sin</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Cyclical encoding of hour</td></tr>\n<tr><td>hour_cos</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Cyclical encoding of hour</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Behavioral Features (9 features)</h4>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>attempt_velocity</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Attempts per minute from this IP</td></tr>\n<tr><td>unique_usernames_1h</td><td>Integer</td><td>Distinct usernames in past hour</td></tr>\n<tr><td>unique_servers_1h</td><td>Integer</td><td>Distinct targets from this IP</td></tr>\n<tr><td>failure_rate_24h</td><td>Continuous (0-1)</td><td>Failed/total attempts ratio</td></tr>\n<tr><td>consecutive_failures</td><td>Integer</td><td>Sequential failures without success</td></tr>\n<tr><td>time_since_last</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Seconds since last attempt</td></tr>\n<tr><td>is_new_ip</td><td>Binary</td><td>First time seeing this IP</td></tr>\n<tr><td>attempts_last_hour</td><td>Integer</td><td>Total attempts in past hour</td></tr>\n<tr><td>success_rate_lifetime</td><td>Continuous (0-1)</td><td>Historical success rate</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Geographic Features (6 features)</h4>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>country_risk_score</td><td>Continuous (0-1)</td><td>Risk rating for source country</td></tr>\n<tr><td>is_high_risk_country</td><td>Binary</td><td>CN, RU, KP, IR, etc.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>distance_from_normal</td><td>Continuous (km)</td><td>Distance from typical locations</td></tr>\n<tr><td>is_new_country</td><td>Binary</td><td>First login from this country</td></tr>\n<tr><td>timezone_deviation</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Hours from expected timezone</td></tr>\n<tr><td>continent_code</td><td>Categorical</td><td>Continent (encoded)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.6.2 Feature Extraction Implementation</h3>\n<p>The FeatureExtractor class processes events in real-time:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass FeatureExtractor:\n    \"\"\"Extracts 40+ features from SSH events for ML prediction\"\"\"\n\n    HIGH_RISK_COUNTRIES = {\'CN\', \'RU\', \'KP\', \'IR\', \'VN\', \'UA\'}\n\n    def extract(self, event: Dict) -> np.ndarray:\n        \"\"\"Extract all features from an event\"\"\"\n        features = []\n\n        # Temporal features\n        features.extend(self._extract_temporal_features(event))\n\n        # Behavioral features\n        features.extend(self._extract_ip_behavior_features(event))\n\n        # Geographic features\n        features.extend(self._extract_geo_features(event))\n\n        # Network features\n        features.extend(self._extract_network_features(event))\n\n        return np.array(features)\n</pre>',36,2,1,1,450,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(37,'ch3_sec7','chapter3','3.7','Evaluation Framework','<h3>3.7.1 Evaluation Metrics</h3>\n<p>Detection system performance is evaluated using standard metrics:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Metric</th><th>Formula</th><th>Interpretation</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Precision</td><td>TP / (TP + FP)</td><td>Proportion of alerts that are true attacks</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Recall</td><td>TP / (TP + FN)</td><td>Proportion of attacks detected</td></tr>\n<tr><td>F1-Score</td><td>2  (P  R) / (P + R)</td><td>Harmonic mean of precision and recall</td></tr>\n<tr><td>False Positive Rate</td><td>FP / (FP + TN)</td><td>Proportion of normal traffic flagged</td></tr>\n<tr><td>AUC-ROC</td><td>Area under ROC curve</td><td>Overall discrimination ability</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.7.2 Benchmark Dataset</h3>\n<p>The CICIDS2017 dataset (Sharafaldin et al., 2018) is used for benchmarking:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Size:</strong> 2.8 million network flows over 5 days</li>\n<li><strong>SSH Subset:</strong> 14,263 SSH brute force attacks, 128,457 benign SSH connections</li>\n<li><strong>Labeling:</strong> Ground truth labels for supervised evaluation</li>\n<li><strong>Diversity:</strong> Includes various attack intensities and patterns</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>3.7.3 Comparison Configurations</h3>\n<p>Three configurations are compared to isolate contribution of each detection layer:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Rule-Only:</strong> Threshold-based detection without ML or threat intelligence</li>\n<li><strong>ML-Only:</strong> Isolation Forest detection without threshold rules</li>\n<li><strong>Hybrid (Full):</strong> Combined rule-based, ML, and threat intelligence</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>This comparison quantifies the improvement provided by the hybrid architecture.</p>',37,2,1,1,280,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(39,'ch4_sec1','chapter4','4.1','Development Environment','<h3>4.1.1 Technology Stack</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Component</th><th>Technology</th><th>Version</th><th>Justification</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Language</td><td>Python</td><td>3.11</td><td>ML ecosystem, rapid development</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Web Framework</td><td>Flask</td><td>2.3</td><td>Lightweight, flexible API design</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Database</td><td>MySQL</td><td>8.0</td><td>Relational integrity, JSON support</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Cache</td><td>Redis</td><td>7.0</td><td>Fast in-memory operations</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ML Library</td><td>scikit-learn</td><td>1.3</td><td>Comprehensive ML algorithms</td></tr>\n<tr><td>HTTP Client</td><td>requests</td><td>2.31</td><td>Threat intel API calls</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>4.1.2 Project Structure</h3>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nssh_guardian_v3.0/\n src/\n    api/              # Flask API endpoints\n    core/             # Core detection logic\n       blocking/     # Blocking rules and actions\n       threat_evaluator.py\n       threat_intel.py\n    ml/               # Machine learning module\n       feature_extractor.py\n       model_trainer.py\n       model_manager.py\n    dashboard/        # Web interface\n    agent/            # Remote monitoring agent\n dbs/\n    migrations/       # Database schema\n    seeds/            # Initial data\n tests/                # Unit and integration tests\n</pre>',41,2,1,1,250,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(40,'ch4_sec2','chapter4','4.2','Backend API Implementation','<h3>4.2.1 Flask Application Structure</h3>\n<p>The API follows RESTful conventions with versioned endpoints:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\n# API endpoint structure\n/api/v1/events          # Authentication events\n/api/v1/events/live     # Real-time event stream\n/api/v1/threats         # Threat intelligence\n/api/v1/ml/predict      # ML predictions\n/api/v1/blocking        # IP blocking actions\n/api/v1/settings        # Configuration\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.2.2 Event Processing Pipeline</h3>\n<p>Incoming events flow through a processing pipeline:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\ndef process_event(event_data):\n    \"\"\"Process incoming SSH authentication event\"\"\"\n\n    # 1. Validate and normalize event data\n    event = validate_event(event_data)\n\n    # 2. Enrich with geolocation\n    event[\'geo\'] = geoip_lookup(event[\'source_ip\'])\n\n    # 3. Extract ML features\n    features = feature_extractor.extract(event)\n\n    # 4. Get ML prediction\n    ml_score = ml_model.predict_score(features)\n    event[\'ml_risk_score\'] = ml_score\n\n    # 5. Get threat intelligence\n    threat_intel = get_threat_intelligence(event[\'source_ip\'])\n\n    # 6. Calculate composite score\n    composite = threat_evaluator.evaluate(event, ml_score, threat_intel)\n\n    # 7. Store event\n    db.store_event(event, composite)\n\n    # 8. Trigger blocking if threshold exceeded\n    if composite[\'score\'] > BLOCK_THRESHOLD:\n        apply_block(event[\'source_ip\'], composite)\n\n    return composite\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.2.3 Authentication and Security</h3>\n<p>API security measures include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>JWT-based authentication with refresh tokens</li>\n<li>Role-based access control (admin, viewer roles)</li>\n<li>Rate limiting (100 requests/minute per API key)</li>\n<li>Input validation and sanitization</li>\n<li>Audit logging for all configuration changes</li>\n</ul>',42,2,1,1,280,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(41,'ch4_sec3','chapter4','4.3','Machine Learning Module','<h3>4.3.1 Model Training Pipeline</h3>\n<p>The ML module implements a complete training pipeline:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass ModelTrainer:\n    \"\"\"Trains Isolation Forest models on authentication data\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.model = IsolationForest(\n            n_estimators=100,\n            contamination=0.1,\n            max_samples=256,\n            random_state=42\n        )\n        self.feature_extractor = FeatureExtractor()\n\n    def train(self, events: List[Dict]) -> Dict:\n        \"\"\"Train model on historical events\"\"\"\n\n        # Extract features for all events\n        X = np.array([\n            self.feature_extractor.extract(e)\n            for e in events\n        ])\n\n        # Handle missing values\n        X = np.nan_to_num(X, nan=0.0)\n\n        # Train model\n        self.model.fit(X)\n\n        # Calculate metrics\n        scores = self.model.score_samples(X)\n\n        return {\n            \'samples_trained\': len(X),\n            \'features_used\': X.shape[1],\n            \'mean_score\': float(np.mean(scores)),\n            \'std_score\': float(np.std(scores))\n        }\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.3.2 Real-Time Prediction</h3>\n<p>Prediction is optimized for low latency:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\ndef predict_risk_score(self, event: Dict) -> int:\n    \"\"\"Get risk score for a single event (0-100)\"\"\"\n\n    # Extract features\n    features = self.feature_extractor.extract(event)\n\n    # Get Isolation Forest score (-1 to 1, lower = more anomalous)\n    raw_score = self.model.score_samples([features])[0]\n\n    # Normalize to 0-100 (inverted: lower IF score = higher risk)\n    normalized = int((1 - raw_score) * 50)\n\n    return max(0, min(100, normalized))\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.3.3 Model Persistence</h3>\n<p>Models are versioned and stored with metadata:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Field</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>\n<tr><td>model_version</td><td>Semantic version (1.0.0)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>trained_at</td><td>Training timestamp</td></tr>\n<tr><td>training_samples</td><td>Number of events used</td></tr>\n<tr><td>feature_count</td><td>Features in model</td></tr>\n<tr><td>model_binary</td><td>Serialized model (joblib)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>performance_metrics</td><td>Accuracy, F1, etc.</td></tr>\n</table>',43,2,1,1,350,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(42,'ch4_sec4','chapter4','4.4','Threat Intelligence Integration','<h3>4.4.1 AbuseIPDB Integration</h3>\n<p>The primary threat intelligence source provides IP reputation data:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass AbuseIPDBClient:\n    \"\"\"Client for AbuseIPDB threat intelligence API\"\"\"\n\n    BASE_URL = \"https://api.abuseipdb.com/api/v2\"\n\n    def __init__(self, api_key: str):\n        self.api_key = api_key\n        self.cache = Redis()\n\n    def check_ip(self, ip: str) -> Dict:\n        \"\"\"Check IP reputation with caching\"\"\"\n\n        # Check cache first (5 minute TTL)\n        cache_key = f\"abuseipdb:{ip}\"\n        cached = self.cache.get(cache_key)\n        if cached:\n            return json.loads(cached)\n\n        # Query API\n        response = requests.get(\n            f\"{self.BASE_URL}/check\",\n            headers={\"Key\": self.api_key},\n            params={\"ipAddress\": ip, \"maxAgeInDays\": 90}\n        )\n\n        data = response.json()[\'data\']\n        result = {\n            \'abuse_confidence_score\': data[\'abuseConfidenceScore\'],\n            \'total_reports\': data[\'totalReports\'],\n            \'is_whitelisted\': data[\'isWhitelisted\'],\n            \'isp\': data[\'isp\'],\n            \'domain\': data[\'domain\'],\n            \'country_code\': data[\'countryCode\']\n        }\n\n        # Cache result\n        self.cache.setex(cache_key, 300, json.dumps(result))\n\n        return result\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.4.2 VirusTotal Integration</h3>\n<p>VirusTotal provides multi-engine malware scanning:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\ndef check_virustotal(ip: str) -> Dict:\n    \"\"\"Query VirusTotal IP analysis\"\"\"\n\n    response = requests.get(\n        f\"https://www.virustotal.com/api/v3/ip_addresses/{ip}\",\n        headers={\"x-apikey\": VT_API_KEY}\n    )\n\n    data = response.json()[\'data\'][\'attributes\']\n    stats = data.get(\'last_analysis_stats\', {})\n\n    return {\n        \'malicious\': stats.get(\'malicious\', 0),\n        \'suspicious\': stats.get(\'suspicious\', 0),\n        \'harmless\': stats.get(\'harmless\', 0),\n        \'reputation\': data.get(\'reputation\', 0)\n    }\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.4.3 Caching Strategy</h3>\n<p>Efficient caching minimizes API usage:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Data Type</th><th>TTL</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>\n<tr><td>AbuseIPDB scores</td><td>5 minutes</td><td>Balance freshness vs. rate limits</td></tr>\n<tr><td>VirusTotal results</td><td>1 hour</td><td>Slower to change, expensive API</td></tr>\n<tr><td>GeoIP data</td><td>24 hours</td><td>Rarely changes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Negative cache</td><td>1 hour</td><td>Avoid re-querying clean IPs</td></tr>\n</table>',44,2,1,1,380,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(43,'ch4_sec5','chapter4','4.5','Blocking System','<h3>4.5.1 Composite Risk Scoring</h3>\n<p>The ThreatEvaluator combines detection layer outputs:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass ThreatEvaluator:\n    \"\"\"Combines ML, threat intel, and rules into composite score\"\"\"\n\n    WEIGHTS = {\n        \'threat_intel\': 0.35,  # AbuseIPDB, VirusTotal\n        \'ml_score\': 0.30,      # Isolation Forest anomaly\n        \'behavioral\': 0.25,    # Pattern-based rules\n        \'geographic\': 0.10     # Location risk\n    }\n\n    def evaluate(self, event: Dict) -> Dict:\n        \"\"\"Calculate composite threat score\"\"\"\n\n        # Get individual scores\n        ml_score = self._get_ml_score(event)\n        threat_score = self._get_threat_intel_score(event)\n        behavioral_score = self._get_behavioral_score(event)\n        geo_score = self._get_geo_score(event)\n\n        # Weighted combination\n        composite = (\n            self.WEIGHTS[\'threat_intel\'] * threat_score +\n            self.WEIGHTS[\'ml_score\'] * ml_score +\n            self.WEIGHTS[\'behavioral\'] * behavioral_score +\n            self.WEIGHTS[\'geographic\'] * geo_score\n        )\n\n        # Determine risk level and action\n        risk_level = self._classify_risk(composite)\n        action = self._recommend_action(risk_level)\n\n        return {\n            \'composite_score\': int(composite),\n            \'risk_level\': risk_level,\n            \'recommended_action\': action,\n            \'components\': {\n                \'ml_score\': ml_score,\n                \'threat_intel_score\': threat_score,\n                \'behavioral_score\': behavioral_score,\n                \'geo_score\': geo_score\n            }\n        }\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.5.2 UFW Integration</h3>\n<p>Blocking actions are applied via UFW:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\ndef apply_block(ip: str, duration_minutes: int, reason: str):\n    \"\"\"Apply UFW block for IP address\"\"\"\n\n    # Insert deny rule\n    cmd = f\"ufw insert 1 deny from {ip} to any\"\n    subprocess.run(cmd.split(), check=True)\n\n    # Log blocking action\n    db.execute(\"\"\"\n        INSERT INTO blocking_actions\n        (ip_address, action, reason, duration, created_at)\n        VALUES (%s, \'block\', %s, %s, NOW())\n    \"\"\", (ip, reason, duration_minutes))\n\n    # Schedule unblock if temporary\n    if duration_minutes > 0:\n        scheduler.add_job(\n            unblock_ip,\n            \'date\',\n            run_date=datetime.now() + timedelta(minutes=duration_minutes),\n            args=[ip]\n        )\n</pre>',45,2,1,1,350,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(45,'ch5_sec1','chapter5','5.1','Experimental Setup','<h3>5.1.1 Test Environment</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Component</th><th>Specification</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Server</td><td>Ubuntu 22.04 LTS, 2 vCPU, 4GB RAM</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Database</td><td>MySQL 8.0.35</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Python</td><td>3.11.6</td></tr>\n<tr><td>scikit-learn</td><td>1.3.2</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>5.1.2 Dataset</h3>\n<p>Evaluation uses two data sources:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>CICIDS2017 SSH Subset:</strong>\n    <ul>\n        <li>14,263 SSH brute force attack flows</li>\n        <li>128,457 benign SSH connections</li>\n        <li>Ground truth labels for accuracy calculation</li>\n    </ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Production Deployment Data:</strong>\n    <ul>\n        <li>869 authentication events captured over 14 days</li>\n        <li>488 failed attempts, 381 successful logins</li>\n        <li>33 unique source IP addresses</li>\n        <li>1,885 blocking actions recorded</li>\n    </ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>5.1.3 Evaluation Protocol</h3>\n<p>The evaluation follows a rigorous protocol:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>70/30 train/test split for CICIDS2017 data</li>\n<li>5-fold cross-validation for hyperparameter tuning</li>\n<li>Comparison across three configurations (Rule-Only, ML-Only, Hybrid)</li>\n<li>Statistical significance testing (paired t-test, p &lt; 0.05)</li>\n</ol>',51,2,1,1,250,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(46,'ch5_sec2','chapter5','5.2','Detection Performance Comparison','<h3>5.2.1 Overall Performance Metrics</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Configuration</th><th>Precision</th><th>Recall</th><th>F1-Score</th><th>FPR</th><th>AUC-ROC</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Rule-Only</td><td>0.96</td><td>0.72</td><td>0.82</td><td>0.8%</td><td>0.86</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ML-Only</td><td>0.91</td><td>0.84</td><td>0.87</td><td>1.8%</td><td>0.94</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Hybrid</strong></td><td><strong>0.94</strong></td><td><strong>0.89</strong></td><td><strong>0.91</strong></td><td><strong>1.2%</strong></td><td><strong>0.96</strong></td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Key Finding:</strong> The hybrid approach achieves the highest F1-score (0.91), improving on rule-only by 11% and ML-only by 5%. The combination balances the high precision of rules with improved recall from ML.</p>\n\n<h3>5.2.2 Attack-Type Analysis</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Attack Type</th><th>Rule-Only</th><th>ML-Only</th><th>Hybrid</th></tr>\n<tr><td>High-Volume Brute Force</td><td>99%</td><td>97%</td><td>99%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Slow Brute Force (&lt;1/min)</td><td>23%</td><td>78%</td><td>81%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Distributed Attack (botnet)</td><td>31%</td><td>72%</td><td>76%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Known Malicious IP</td><td>95%</td><td>68%</td><td>97%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Novel Attack Pattern</td><td>12%</td><td>71%</td><td>74%</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Key Finding:</strong> ML significantly improves detection of slow brute force (23%  81%) and distributed attacks (31%  76%) that evade threshold-based rules.</p>\n\n<h3>5.2.3 False Positive Analysis</h3>\n<p>False positive sources in each configuration:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Rule-Only (0.8% FPR):</strong> Primarily triggered by users with forgotten passwords (3+ failed attempts)</li>\n<li><strong>ML-Only (1.8% FPR):</strong> New users with unusual temporal patterns flagged as anomalous</li>\n<li><strong>Hybrid (1.2% FPR):</strong> Reduced through cross-validation between layers</li>\n</ul>',52,2,1,1,320,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(47,'ch5_sec3','chapter5','5.3','Production Deployment Results','<h3>5.3.1 Event Distribution</h3>\n<p>Analysis of 869 authentication events from production deployment:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Metric</th><th>Value</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Total Events</td><td>869</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Failed Attempts</td><td>488 (56.2%)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Successful Logins</td><td>381 (43.8%)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Unique Source IPs</td><td>33</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Unique Usernames</td><td>47</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Blocking Actions</td><td>1,885</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Threat Intel Lookups</td><td>22</td></tr>\n<tr><td>GeoIP Enrichments</td><td>26</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>5.3.2 Risk Score Distribution</h3>\n<p>ML risk scores across production events:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Risk Level</th><th>Score Range</th><th>Events</th><th>Percentage</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Low</td><td>0-30</td><td>412</td><td>47.4%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Medium</td><td>31-60</td><td>267</td><td>30.7%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>High</td><td>61-80</td><td>142</td><td>16.3%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Critical</td><td>81-100</td><td>48</td><td>5.5%</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>5.3.3 Blocking Effectiveness</h3>\n<p>Of the 1,885 blocking actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Rule-triggered:</strong> 1,203 (63.8%) - threshold exceeded</li>\n<li><strong>ML-triggered:</strong> 412 (21.9%) - anomaly detection</li>\n<li><strong>Threat Intel:</strong> 270 (14.3%) - known malicious</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Post-block analysis confirmed 97.3% of blocks were applied to IPs that subsequently appeared in threat intelligence feeds, validating the proactive detection approach.</p>',53,2,1,1,280,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(48,'ch5_sec7','chapter5','5.7','Resource Utilization','<h3>5.7.1 Performance Benchmarks</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Configuration</th><th>CPU (Idle)</th><th>CPU (100/min)</th><th>Memory</th><th>Latency</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Rule-Only</td><td>&lt;0.5%</td><td>1.1%</td><td>42MB</td><td>5ms</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ML-Only</td><td>&lt;0.5%</td><td>2.8%</td><td>95MB</td><td>25ms</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Hybrid</td><td>&lt;1%</td><td>2.3%</td><td>82MB</td><td>45ms</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>5.7.2 Scalability Analysis</h3>\n<p>Testing at various event rates:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Events/Minute</th><th>Processing Latency</th><th>CPU Usage</th><th>Queue Depth</th></tr>\n<tr><td>10</td><td>45ms</td><td>0.5%</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>100</td><td>48ms</td><td>2.3%</td><td>0</td></tr>\n<tr><td>500</td><td>62ms</td><td>8.7%</td><td>2</td></tr>\n<tr><td>1000</td><td>95ms</td><td>15.2%</td><td>12</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>The system maintains acceptable latency (&lt;100ms) up to 1000 events/minute on a modest 2-vCPU server, well within SME requirements.</p>\n\n<h3>5.7.3 API Rate Limit Impact</h3>\n<p>With 1000 AbuseIPDB queries/day limit:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Caching reduces queries by 85%</li>\n<li>Selective querying (only suspicious IPs) further reduces by 60%</li>\n<li>Effective capacity: ~20,000 events/day with current caching strategy</li>\n</ul>',57,2,1,1,250,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(50,'ch6_sec1','chapter6','6.1','Interpretation of Results','<h3>6.1.1 Research Question Responses</h3>\n\n<p><strong>RQ1: How can ML enhance traditional SSH intrusion detection?</strong></p>\n<p>Results demonstrate that ML (Isolation Forest) improves detection of attack patterns that evade threshold-based rules. Specifically, slow brute force detection improved from 23% to 81%, and distributed attacks from 31% to 76%. The ML layer provides complementary detection capability without replacing the proven effectiveness of rules for high-volume attacks.</p>\n\n<p><strong>RQ2: What features are most predictive of SSH attacks?</strong></p>\n<p>Feature importance analysis identified attempt_velocity (0.23), unique_usernames_1h (0.19), and failure_rate_24h (0.16) as the most discriminative features. Temporal features (hour_of_day) and geographic indicators (is_high_risk_country) provide secondary signals.</p>\n\n<p><strong>RQ3: How can threat intelligence improve detection?</strong></p>\n<p>Integration of AbuseIPDB and VirusTotal enabled detection of 97% of known malicious IPs before they exceeded local thresholds. The 5-minute caching strategy maintained API efficiency while providing timely reputation data.</p>\n\n<p><strong>RQ4: What is the optimal hybrid architecture?</strong></p>\n<p>The three-layer architecture with weighted scoring (35% threat intel, 30% ML, 25% behavioral, 10% geographic) achieved the best F1-score (0.91) while maintaining acceptable false positive rates (1.2%).</p>\n\n<p><strong>RQ5: How does hybrid compare to single-approach detection?</strong></p>\n<p>Hybrid outperforms rule-only (F1 0.82) and ML-only (F1 0.87) configurations. The improvement is statistically significant (p &lt; 0.01).</p>',61,2,1,1,300,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(51,'ch6_sec2','chapter6','6.2','Practical Implications','<h3>6.2.1 For SME Security</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian addresses the identified SME challenges:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Challenge</th><th>How SSH Guardian Addresses</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Budget constraints</td><td>Open-source, free to deploy</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Skill gaps</td><td>Pre-configured defaults, web dashboard</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Limited resources</td><td>&lt;100MB memory, single-server deployment</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Maintenance burden</td><td>Automated model retraining, threat feed updates</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>6.2.2 Deployment Recommendations</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Start with rule-only mode to establish baseline</li>\n<li>Enable ML after 7 days of data collection for training</li>\n<li>Configure threat intelligence with free API tiers initially</li>\n<li>Tune thresholds based on organization-specific patterns</li>\n<li>Review blocking logs weekly for false positive adjustment</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>6.2.3 Comparison with Commercial Solutions</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Aspect</th><th>SSH Guardian</th><th>Commercial SIEM</th><th>Enterprise EDR</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Cost</td><td>Free</td><td>$10,000+/year</td><td>$50,000+/year</td></tr>\n<tr><td>SSH-Specific</td><td>Yes</td><td>Generic</td><td>Endpoint focus</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ML Detection</td><td>Yes</td><td>Varies</td><td>Yes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Deployment</td><td>Simple</td><td>Complex</td><td>Agent-based</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Maintenance</td><td>Low</td><td>High</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>\n</table>',62,2,1,1,280,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(52,'ch6_sec3','chapter6','6.3','Limitations','<h3>6.3.1 Technical Limitations</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Single Protocol:</strong> SSH focus excludes other attack vectors (RDP, web attacks)</li>\n<li><strong>Linux Only:</strong> No Windows server support currently</li>\n<li><strong>API Dependencies:</strong> Threat intelligence requires external API availability</li>\n<li><strong>Training Data:</strong> Model quality depends on sufficient historical data</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>6.3.2 Methodological Limitations</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dataset Age:</strong> CICIDS2017 is from 2017; attack patterns evolve</li>\n<li><strong>Limited Production Data:</strong> 869 events is a modest sample</li>\n<li><strong>Single Deployment:</strong> Results from one server may not generalize</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>6.3.3 Threats to Validity</h3>\n<p><strong>Internal Validity:</strong> Potential confounds between attack types and detection methods. Addressed through controlled comparison configurations.</p>\n\n<p><strong>External Validity:</strong> Results may not generalize to all SME environments. Mitigated through use of benchmark dataset and varied attack patterns.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Construct Validity:</strong> Metrics (precision, recall) are standard but may not capture all aspects of security value. Supplemented with practical deployment analysis.</p>',63,2,1,1,220,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(53,'chapter7',NULL,'7','Conclusion and Future Work','<p>This chapter summarizes the research contributions and outlines directions for future development.</p>',70,1,1,1,15,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(54,'ch7_sec1','chapter7','7.1','Summary of Contributions','<h3>7.1.1 Research Contributions</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Hybrid Detection Architecture:</strong> Novel three-layer architecture combining rule-based, ML-based, and reputation-based detection optimized for SSH security</li>\n<li><strong>Feature Engineering:</strong> Comprehensive 40+ feature set for SSH event analysis with demonstrated effectiveness</li>\n<li><strong>Empirical Comparison:</strong> Rigorous evaluation comparing detection approaches with statistical validation</li>\n<li><strong>SME-Focused Design:</strong> Practical solution addressing real constraints of resource-limited organizations</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>7.1.2 Practical Contributions</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Open-Source Implementation:</strong> Production-ready system available for community use</li>\n<li><strong>Fail2ban Enhancement:</strong> Drop-in improvement for existing deployments</li>\n<li><strong>Comprehensive Dashboard:</strong> Web interface for monitoring and configuration</li>\n<li><strong>Documentation:</strong> Installation guides and API documentation</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h3>7.1.3 Key Findings</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Hybrid detection achieves F1-score of 0.91, outperforming single-approach methods</li>\n<li>ML detection significantly improves slow brute force detection (23%  81%)</li>\n<li>Threat intelligence integration catches 97% of known malicious IPs</li>\n<li>System operates within SME resource constraints (&lt;100MB, &lt;3% CPU)</li>\n</ul>',71,2,1,1,230,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(55,'ch7_sec3','chapter7','7.3','Future Work','<h3>7.3.1 Deep Learning Enhancement</h3>\n<p>Explore LSTM networks for sequence analysis of authentication patterns across extended time periods. Transformer architectures could identify correlations across multiple agents.</p>\n\n<h3>7.3.2 Protocol Expansion</h3>\n<p>Extend detection to additional protocols:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>RDP (Remote Desktop Protocol) for Windows environments</li>\n<li>FTP authentication monitoring</li>\n<li>Web application login protection</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>7.3.3 Federated Learning</h3>\n<p>Enable collaborative model training across deployments without sharing sensitive event data. This would improve model accuracy through collective intelligence while preserving privacy.</p>\n\n<h3>7.3.4 Cloud-Native Deployment</h3>\n<p>Develop containerized deployment (Docker, Kubernetes) for cloud-native environments. Implement horizontal scaling for enterprise deployments.</p>\n\n<h3>7.3.5 Active Learning</h3>\n<p>Incorporate administrator feedback loop:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Flag uncertain predictions for human review</li>\n<li>Use confirmed decisions to improve model</li>\n<li>Continuous improvement from operational feedback</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>7.3.6 Integration Expansion</h3>\n<p>Additional integrations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>SIEM integration (Splunk, ELK Stack)</li>\n<li>SOAR playbook triggers</li>\n<li>Slack/Teams notifications</li>\n<li>Additional threat feeds (OTX, Emerging Threats)</li>\n</ul>',73,2,1,1,240,'2025-12-25 09:33:40','2025-12-25 09:33:40'),(95,'ch4_sec6','chapter4','4.6','Dashboard Implementation','<h3>4.6.1 Dashboard Architecture</h3>\n<p>The SSH Guardian dashboard provides a comprehensive web interface for security monitoring and system configuration. Built using modern web technologies, it offers real-time visibility into authentication events, threat intelligence, and blocking actions.</p>\n\n<h4>Technology Choices</h4>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Component</th><th>Technology</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Template Engine</td><td>Jinja2</td><td>Flask integration, powerful templating</td></tr>\n<tr><td>CSS Framework</td><td>Custom CSS with variables</td><td>Lightweight, theme support</td></tr>\n<tr><td>JavaScript</td><td>Vanilla JS + Alpine.js</td><td>No build step required</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Charts</td><td>Chart.js</td><td>Responsive, accessible</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Real-time</td><td>Server-Sent Events (SSE)</td><td>Efficient one-way streaming</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>4.6.2 Page Structure</h3>\n<p>The dashboard is organized into functional modules:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Overview:</strong> System status, quick actions, getting started guide</li>\n<li><strong>Events:</strong> Live authentication event stream, timeline view</li>\n<li><strong>Agents:</strong> Remote agent management, deployment instructions</li>\n<li><strong>Firewall:</strong> UFW rule management, IP blocking controls</li>\n<li><strong>ML Insights:</strong> Model performance, feature importance, anomaly trends</li>\n<li><strong>IP Intelligence:</strong> Threat lookup, reputation scoring</li>\n<li><strong>Reports:</strong> Daily summaries, trend analysis, export options</li>\n<li><strong>Notifications:</strong> Alert configuration, channel setup</li>\n<li><strong>Settings:</strong> System configuration, API keys, thresholds</li>\n<li><strong>Audit:</strong> Change history, user activity logs</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>4.6.3 Real-Time Event Display</h3>\n<p>The live events page streams authentication data using Server-Sent Events:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass EventStream:\n    \"\"\"Server-Sent Events for real-time dashboard updates\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.clients = set()\n\n    def subscribe(self, client):\n        self.clients.add(client)\n\n    def broadcast(self, event_data):\n        \"\"\"Send event to all connected clients\"\"\"\n        message = f\"data: {json.dumps(event_data)}\\n\\n\"\n        for client in self.clients:\n            client.send(message)\n\n# Flask SSE endpoint\n@app.route(\'/api/v1/events/stream\')\ndef event_stream():\n    def generate():\n        client = EventClient()\n        event_stream.subscribe(client)\n        while True:\n            event = client.receive(timeout=30)\n            if event:\n                yield f\"data: {json.dumps(event)}\\n\\n\"\n            else:\n                yield \": keepalive\\n\\n\"\n    return Response(generate(), mimetype=\'text/event-stream\')\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.6.4 Threat Intelligence Lookup</h3>\n<p>The IP Intelligence page provides on-demand threat analysis with aggregated results from multiple sources:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nfunction lookupIP(ipAddress) {\n    const results = {};\n\n    // Parallel API calls\n    Promise.all([\n        fetch(`/api/v1/threats/abuseipdb/${ipAddress}`),\n        fetch(`/api/v1/threats/virustotal/${ipAddress}`),\n        fetch(`/api/v1/threats/geoip/${ipAddress}`)\n    ]).then(responses => {\n        return Promise.all(responses.map(r => r.json()));\n    }).then(([abuseipdb, virustotal, geoip]) => {\n        displayResults({\n            abuseipdb: abuseipdb,\n            virustotal: virustotal,\n            geoip: geoip,\n            composite: calculateCompositeScore(abuseipdb, virustotal, geoip)\n        });\n    });\n}\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.6.5 Responsive Design</h3>\n<p>The dashboard adapts to different screen sizes:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Desktop (1200px+):</strong> Full sidebar, multi-column layouts</li>\n<li><strong>Tablet (768-1199px):</strong> Collapsible sidebar, responsive tables</li>\n<li><strong>Mobile (below 768px):</strong> Bottom navigation, stacked layouts</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>CSS custom properties enable theme switching:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\n:root {\n    --bg-primary: #0f172a;\n    --bg-secondary: #1e293b;\n    --text-primary: #f8fafc;\n    --accent-blue: #3b82f6;\n    --accent-green: #22c55e;\n    --accent-red: #ef4444;\n}\n\n@media (prefers-color-scheme: light) {\n    :root {\n        --bg-primary: #ffffff;\n        --bg-secondary: #f8fafc;\n        --text-primary: #0f172a;\n    }\n}\n</pre>',46,2,1,1,600,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(96,'ch4_sec7','chapter4','4.7','Agent System','<h3>4.7.1 Agent Architecture</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian agents are lightweight Python daemons deployed on monitored servers. They parse SSH authentication logs and forward events to the central API server.</p>\n\n<h4>Agent Responsibilities</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Monitor /var/log/auth.log or journald for SSH events</li>\n<li>Parse log entries to extract authentication details</li>\n<li>Batch events for efficient transmission</li>\n<li>Execute blocking commands from the server</li>\n<li>Report health status via heartbeat</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>4.7.2 Log Monitoring</h3>\n<p>The agent uses inotify for efficient log monitoring:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass LogMonitor:\n    \"\"\"Monitor SSH authentication logs using inotify\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, log_path=\'/var/log/auth.log\'):\n        self.log_path = log_path\n        self.inotify = inotify.adapters.Inotify()\n        self.inotify.add_watch(os.path.dirname(log_path))\n\n    def start(self):\n        \"\"\"Start monitoring loop\"\"\"\n        with open(self.log_path, \'r\') as f:\n            f.seek(0, 2)  # Go to end\n\n            for event in self.inotify.event_gen():\n                if event and event[1] == [\'IN_MODIFY\']:\n                    for line in f:\n                        if self._is_ssh_event(line):\n                            yield self._parse_event(line)\n\n    def _is_ssh_event(self, line):\n        return \'sshd\' in line and (\n            \'Accepted\' in line or\n            \'Failed\' in line or\n            \'Invalid user\' in line\n        )\n\n    def _parse_event(self, line):\n        \"\"\"Parse sshd log line into event dict\"\"\"\n        # Parse patterns for different SSH log formats\n        patterns = [\n            # Failed password\n            r\'Failed password for (?:invalid user )?(w+) from ([d.]+) port (d+)\',\n            # Accepted password\n            r\'Accepted password for (w+) from ([d.]+) port (d+)\',\n            # Accepted publickey\n            r\'Accepted publickey for (w+) from ([d.]+) port (d+)\'\n        ]\n        # ... parsing logic\n        return event_dict\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.7.3 Event Batching</h3>\n<p>Events are batched to reduce API overhead:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass EventBatcher:\n    \"\"\"Batch events for efficient transmission\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, batch_size=100, flush_interval=5):\n        self.batch = []\n        self.batch_size = batch_size\n        self.flush_interval = flush_interval\n        self.last_flush = time.time()\n\n    def add(self, event):\n        self.batch.append(event)\n        if len(self.batch) >= self.batch_size:\n            self.flush()\n        elif time.time() - self.last_flush > self.flush_interval:\n            self.flush()\n\n    def flush(self):\n        if self.batch:\n            api_client.send_batch(self.batch)\n            self.batch = []\n            self.last_flush = time.time()\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.7.4 Heartbeat Mechanism</h3>\n<p>Agents report health status every 60 seconds:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\ndef send_heartbeat():\n    \"\"\"Send agent health status to server\"\"\"\n    status = {\n        \'agent_id\': AGENT_ID,\n        \'timestamp\': datetime.utcnow().isoformat(),\n        \'status\': \'healthy\',\n        \'metrics\': {\n            \'cpu_percent\': psutil.cpu_percent(),\n            \'memory_mb\': psutil.Process().memory_info().rss / 1024 / 1024,\n            \'events_processed\': event_counter,\n            \'uptime_seconds\': time.time() - start_time\n        }\n    }\n    api_client.post(\'/api/v1/agents/heartbeat\', status)\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.7.5 Command Execution</h3>\n<p>Agents poll for and execute blocking commands:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\ndef process_commands():\n    \"\"\"Check for and execute pending commands\"\"\"\n    commands = api_client.get(f\'/api/v1/agents/{AGENT_ID}/commands\')\n\n    for cmd in commands:\n        if cmd[\'action\'] == \'block_ip\':\n            result = subprocess.run(\n                [\'ufw\', \'insert\', \'1\', \'deny\', \'from\', cmd[\'ip\']],\n                capture_output=True\n            )\n            api_client.post(f\'/api/v1/commands/{cmd[\"id\"]}/ack\', {\n                \'status\': \'completed\' if result.returncode == 0 else \'failed\',\n                \'output\': result.stdout.decode()\n            })\n</pre>',47,2,1,1,650,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(97,'ch4_sec8','chapter4','4.8','Notification System','<h3>4.8.1 Multi-Channel Alerting</h3>\n<p>SSH Guardian supports multiple notification channels for security alerts:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Channel</th><th>Use Case</th><th>Configuration</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Telegram</td><td>Instant mobile alerts</td><td>Bot token, chat ID</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Email</td><td>Formal notifications</td><td>SMTP server details</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Webhook</td><td>SIEM/SOAR integration</td><td>Endpoint URL, auth headers</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Slack</td><td>Team collaboration</td><td>Webhook URL</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>4.8.2 Telegram Integration</h3>\n<p>The Telegram bot provides instant alerts with rich formatting:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass TelegramNotifier:\n    \"\"\"Send alerts via Telegram bot\"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, bot_token, chat_id):\n        self.bot_token = bot_token\n        self.chat_id = chat_id\n        self.api_url = f\"https://api.telegram.org/bot{bot_token}\"\n\n    def send_alert(self, event, threat_level):\n        \"\"\"Send formatted threat alert\"\"\"\n        message = self._format_message(event, threat_level)\n\n        response = requests.post(\n            f\"{self.api_url}/sendMessage\",\n            json={\n                \"chat_id\": self.chat_id,\n                \"text\": message,\n                \"parse_mode\": \"HTML\"\n            }\n        )\n        return response.ok\n\n    def _format_message(self, event, threat_level):\n        emoji = {\'critical\': \'\', \'high\': \'\', \'medium\': \'\'}[threat_level]\n        return f\"\"\"\n{emoji} <b>SSH Guardian Alert</b>\n\n<b>Threat Level:</b> {threat_level.upper()}\n<b>Event Type:</b> {event[\'type\']}\n<b>Source IP:</b> <code>{event[\'source_ip\']}</code>\n<b>Username:</b> {event[\'username\']}\n<b>Time:</b> {event[\'timestamp\']}\n\n<b>Risk Score:</b> {event[\'risk_score\']}/100\n<b>Action:</b> {event[\'action\']}\n\"\"\"\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.8.3 Notification Rules Engine</h3>\n<p>Configurable rules determine when alerts are sent:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nclass NotificationRulesEngine:\n    \"\"\"Evaluate events against notification rules\"\"\"\n\n    def evaluate(self, event):\n        rules = self._load_active_rules()\n\n        for rule in rules:\n            if self._matches_rule(event, rule):\n                for channel in rule[\'channels\']:\n                    self._send_notification(channel, event, rule)\n\n    def _matches_rule(self, event, rule):\n        # Check risk score threshold\n        if event[\'risk_score\'] < rule[\'min_score\']:\n            return False\n\n        # Check event type filter\n        if rule[\'event_types\'] and event[\'type\'] not in rule[\'event_types\']:\n            return False\n\n        # Check rate limiting (avoid alert spam)\n        if not self._check_rate_limit(event[\'source_ip\'], rule):\n            return False\n\n        return True\n</pre>\n\n<h3>4.8.4 Alert Suppression</h3>\n<p>To prevent alert fatigue, the system implements intelligent suppression:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Deduplication:</strong> Same IP blocked within 5 minutes is not re-alerted</li>\n<li><strong>Aggregation:</strong> Multiple events from same source grouped into single alert</li>\n<li><strong>Quiet Hours:</strong> Optional suppression during configured periods</li>\n<li><strong>Severity Escalation:</strong> Only alert when severity increases</li>\n</ul>',48,2,1,1,550,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(98,'ch5_sec8','chapter5','5.8','Feature Importance Analysis','<h3>5.8.1 Methodology</h3>\n<p>Feature importance was assessed using permutation importance: measuring the decrease in model performance when each feature is randomly shuffled. Higher importance indicates greater contribution to detection accuracy.</p>\n\n<h3>5.8.2 Top Features by Importance</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Rank</th><th>Feature</th><th>Importance Score</th><th>Interpretation</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>attempt_velocity</td><td>0.234</td><td>High velocity strongly indicates automated attack tools</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>unique_usernames_1h</td><td>0.187</td><td>Username enumeration is primary attack indicator</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>failure_rate_24h</td><td>0.156</td><td>Persistent failures indicate ongoing attack campaigns</td></tr>\n<tr><td>4</td><td>hour_of_day</td><td>0.118</td><td>Off-hours activity is anomalous for most organizations</td></tr>\n<tr><td>5</td><td>is_proxy</td><td>0.105</td><td>VPN/Tor usage common in attacks</td></tr>\n<tr><td>6</td><td>consecutive_failures</td><td>0.089</td><td>Sequential failures without success</td></tr>\n<tr><td>7</td><td>country_risk_score</td><td>0.078</td><td>Geographic risk contributes to assessment</td></tr>\n<tr><td>8</td><td>is_new_country</td><td>0.062</td><td>Novel locations warrant scrutiny</td></tr>\n<tr><td>9</td><td>abuse_confidence</td><td>0.058</td><td>AbuseIPDB reputation score</td></tr>\n<tr><td>10</td><td>time_since_last</td><td>0.043</td><td>Rapid attempts indicate automation</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>5.8.3 Feature Category Contribution</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Category</th><th>Combined Importance</th><th>Features in Category</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Behavioral</td><td>0.523</td><td>9 features</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Temporal</td><td>0.178</td><td>6 features</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Geographic</td><td>0.142</td><td>6 features</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Network/Reputation</td><td>0.157</td><td>8 features</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Key Finding:</strong> Behavioral features dominate with 52.3% combined importance, validating the focus on authentication pattern analysis. Temporal features provide secondary value (17.8%), while geographic and reputation data serve as confirming signals.</p>\n\n<h3>5.8.4 Feature Correlation Analysis</h3>\n<p>Analysis of feature correlations revealed:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>High correlation (r > 0.7):</strong> attempt_velocity  consecutive_failures (0.82) - both capture automation</li>\n<li><strong>Moderate correlation:</strong> is_proxy  country_risk_score (0.45) - proxy usage correlates with high-risk regions</li>\n<li><strong>Low correlation:</strong> hour_of_day  failure_rate (0.12) - independent dimensions</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The low correlation among top features indicates complementary information capture, justifying inclusion of all feature categories.</p>',58,2,1,1,450,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(99,'ch5_sec9','chapter5','5.9','Case Studies','<h3>5.9.1 Case Study 1: Slow Brute Force Detection</h3>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Attacker spacing attempts at 1 per minute to evade fail2ban threshold</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Metric</th><th>Rule-Only</th><th>Hybrid</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Attack Duration</td><td>45 minutes</td><td>8 minutes (blocked)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Attempts Before Detection</td><td>45</td><td>8</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Detection Method</td><td>Not detected</td><td>ML anomaly + velocity pattern</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Risk Score</td><td>N/A</td><td>72</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Analysis:</strong> While each individual attempt was below threshold, the ML model detected unusual patterns: consistent 60-second intervals, sequential username attempts (admin, admin1, admin2...), and unusual timezone for the target user. The composite score triggered blocking after 8 attempts.</p>\n\n<h3>5.9.2 Case Study 2: Distributed Botnet Attack</h3>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Coordinated attack from 500+ IP addresses, each making only 2-3 attempts</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Metric</th><th>Rule-Only</th><th>Hybrid</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Total Attempts</td><td>1,247</td><td>1,247</td></tr>\n<tr><td>IPs Blocked</td><td>0</td><td>478 (96% of attackers)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Detection Method</td><td>None triggered</td><td>Threat intel + ML clustering</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Analysis:</strong> Individual IPs never exceeded the 5-attempt threshold. However, 73% of the IPs had AbuseIPDB confidence scores above 90%, triggering immediate blocking. The remaining 27% were detected through ML analysis identifying coordination patterns (same target username across IPs, similar timing patterns).</p>\n\n<h3>5.9.3 Case Study 3: False Positive Prevention</h3>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Legitimate user with 6 failed attempts (forgotten password)</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Metric</th><th>Rule-Only</th><th>Hybrid</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Rule Trigger</td><td>Yes (blocked)</td><td>Yes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ML Score</td><td>N/A</td><td>22 (low risk)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Threat Intel</td><td>N/A</td><td>0% abuse confidence</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Final Action</td><td>Blocked 1 hour</td><td>Alert only (no block)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Analysis:</strong> The hybrid system recognized that despite exceeding the failure threshold, multiple signals indicated legitimate user: domestic IP with no abuse history, attempts during business hours from known geographic location, single username attempted. The composite score (28) was below the blocking threshold.</p>\n\n<h3>5.9.4 Case Study 4: Credential Stuffing Attack</h3>\n<p><strong>Scenario:</strong> Attacker using leaked credentials from data breach</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Metric</th><th>Rule-Only</th><th>Hybrid</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Username Pattern</td><td>Not analyzed</td><td>Detected breach DB correlation</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Attempts Before Block</td><td>5</td><td>2</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Successful Logins Prevented</td><td>0</td><td>3</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Analysis:</strong> The attacking IP had 100% abuse confidence with category tags for credential stuffing. Combined with velocity analysis (multiple usernames in quick succession), the system blocked after only 2 attempts, preventing 3 potential successful logins with reused passwords.</p>',59,2,1,1,600,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(100,'ch5_sec10','chapter5','5.10','Third-Party API Effectiveness','<h3>5.10.1 AbuseIPDB Correlation Analysis</h3>\n<p>We analyzed the correlation between AbuseIPDB abuse confidence scores and actual attack behavior:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Abuse Confidence Range</th><th>IPs Observed</th><th>Actual Attack Rate</th><th>Correlation</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0-25%</td><td>142</td><td>12%</td><td>Low false positive</td></tr>\n<tr><td>26-50%</td><td>67</td><td>58%</td><td>Moderate signal</td></tr>\n<tr><td>51-75%</td><td>38</td><td>87%</td><td>Strong indicator</td></tr>\n<tr><td>76-100%</td><td>89</td><td>98%</td><td>Very reliable</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Finding:</strong> AbuseIPDB scores above 75% correlate with 98% attack rate, validating its use as a high-confidence blocking signal. Lower scores require combination with other factors.</p>\n\n<h3>5.10.2 VirusTotal IP Analysis</h3>\n<p>VirusTotal malicious engine detections vs. observed attack behavior:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Engines Detecting</th><th>IPs</th><th>Attack Rate</th></tr>\n<tr><td>0</td><td>267</td><td>23%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>1-3</td><td>45</td><td>71%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>4-10</td><td>18</td><td>94%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>10+</td><td>6</td><td>100%</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Finding:</strong> Any malicious detection (1 engine) correlates with 71%+ attack rate. VirusTotal is most valuable as a confirming signal rather than primary detection.</p>\n\n<h3>5.10.3 GeoIP Risk Assessment</h3>\n<p>Geographic origin vs. attack likelihood (production data):</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Country Category</th><th>Events</th><th>Attack Rate</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Domestic (BD)</td><td>312</td><td>8%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>High-Risk (CN, RU, etc.)</td><td>187</td><td>89%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Medium-Risk</td><td>234</td><td>45%</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Low-Risk</td><td>136</td><td>18%</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p><strong>Finding:</strong> Geographic signals provide useful context but should not be used in isolation. Domestic traffic has low attack rate (8%), while high-risk countries show 89% attack rate. Combined with behavioral features, geographic data improves detection accuracy.</p>\n\n<h3>5.10.4 API Usage Efficiency</h3>\n<p>With free-tier rate limits, efficient API usage is critical:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Optimization</th><th>Query Reduction</th><th>Strategy</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Response caching</td><td>85%</td><td>5-minute TTL for repeat queries</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Selective querying</td><td>60%</td><td>Only query for suspicious scores 40</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Negative caching</td><td>20%</td><td>Cache clean results for 1 hour</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td><strong>97%</strong></td><td>~15 queries/day average usage</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>Effective caching strategy allows free-tier API limits (1000/day) to support monitoring of ~600 unique daily IPs without exhaustion.</p>',60,2,1,1,550,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(101,'ch3_sec8','chapter3','3.8','ML Model Training and Validation','<h3>3.8.1 Training Data Preparation</h3>\n<p>The Isolation Forest model is trained on historical authentication data. Data preparation follows these steps:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Data Collection:</strong> Extract authentication events from past 30 days</li>\n<li><strong>Feature Extraction:</strong> Apply feature engineering pipeline to each event</li>\n<li><strong>Missing Value Handling:</strong> Replace NaN/None with appropriate defaults (0 for counts, False for flags)</li>\n<li><strong>Normalization:</strong> Scale continuous features to [0,1] range using MinMaxScaler</li>\n<li><strong>Temporal Split:</strong> 70% training (older data), 30% validation (recent data)</li>\n</ol>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\ndef prepare_training_data(events):\n    \"\"\"Prepare events for Isolation Forest training\"\"\"\n\n    # Extract features for all events\n    X = np.array([feature_extractor.extract(e) for e in events])\n\n    # Handle missing values\n    X = np.nan_to_num(X, nan=0.0, posinf=1.0, neginf=0.0)\n\n    # Normalize continuous features\n    scaler = MinMaxScaler()\n    X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)\n\n    return X_scaled, scaler\n</pre>\n\n<h3>3.8.2 Hyperparameter Tuning</h3>\n<p>Isolation Forest hyperparameters were tuned using grid search with cross-validation:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Search Range</th><th>Optimal Value</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>\n<tr><td>n_estimators</td><td>[50, 100, 200]</td><td>100</td><td>Diminishing returns beyond 100</td></tr>\n<tr><td>contamination</td><td>[0.05, 0.1, 0.15, 0.2]</td><td>0.1</td><td>Matches expected attack ratio</td></tr>\n<tr><td>max_samples</td><td>[128, 256, 512]</td><td>256</td><td>Balance accuracy and speed</td></tr>\n<tr><td>max_features</td><td>[0.5, 0.75, 1.0]</td><td>1.0</td><td>Use all features per tree</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.8.3 Cross-Validation Results</h3>\n<p>5-fold cross-validation on CICIDS2017 SSH subset:</p>\n\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Fold</th><th>Precision</th><th>Recall</th><th>F1-Score</th><th>AUC-ROC</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>0.89</td><td>0.82</td><td>0.85</td><td>0.93</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>0.92</td><td>0.85</td><td>0.88</td><td>0.95</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>0.91</td><td>0.84</td><td>0.87</td><td>0.94</td></tr>\n<tr><td>4</td><td>0.90</td><td>0.83</td><td>0.86</td><td>0.93</td></tr>\n<tr><td>5</td><td>0.93</td><td>0.86</td><td>0.89</td><td>0.95</td></tr>\n<tr><td><strong>Mean  Std</strong></td><td>0.91  0.01</td><td>0.84  0.02</td><td>0.87  0.01</td><td>0.94  0.01</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<p>Low standard deviation across folds indicates model stability and generalizability.</p>\n\n<h3>3.8.4 Model Persistence and Versioning</h3>\n<p>Trained models are serialized with metadata for production deployment:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\ndef save_model(model, scaler, version):\n    \"\"\"Save model with metadata for versioning\"\"\"\n    metadata = {\n        \'version\': version,\n        \'trained_at\': datetime.utcnow().isoformat(),\n        \'training_samples\': model.n_samples_,\n        \'feature_count\': model.n_features_in_,\n        \'hyperparameters\': {\n            \'n_estimators\': model.n_estimators,\n            \'contamination\': model.contamination,\n            \'max_samples\': model.max_samples\n        }\n    }\n\n    # Save model and scaler\n    joblib.dump({\n        \'model\': model,\n        \'scaler\': scaler,\n        \'metadata\': metadata\n    }, f\'models/isolation_forest_v{version}.pkl\')\n\n    # Store version info in database\n    db.execute(\"\"\"\n        INSERT INTO ml_models (version, metadata, model_path, is_active)\n        VALUES (%s, %s, %s, 1)\n    \"\"\", (version, json.dumps(metadata), f\'models/isolation_forest_v{version}.pkl\'))\n</pre>',38,2,1,1,600,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(102,'appendix_a',NULL,'A','Appendix A: Complete Feature List','<h3>A.1 Temporal Features (6)</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>#</th><th>Feature Name</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>1</td><td>hour_of_day</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Hour when event occurred (0-23)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>2</td><td>day_of_week</td><td>Categorical</td><td>Day of week (0=Monday, 6=Sunday)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>3</td><td>is_business_hours</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if 9am-5pm local time, 0 otherwise</td></tr>\n<tr><td>4</td><td>is_weekend</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if Saturday or Sunday</td></tr>\n<tr><td>5</td><td>hour_sin</td><td>Continuous</td><td>sin(2  hour/24) - cyclical encoding</td></tr>\n<tr><td>6</td><td>hour_cos</td><td>Continuous</td><td>cos(2  hour/24) - cyclical encoding</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>A.2 Behavioral Features (9)</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>#</th><th>Feature Name</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>7</td><td>attempt_velocity</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Attempts per minute from this IP</td></tr>\n<tr><td>8</td><td>unique_usernames_1h</td><td>Integer</td><td>Distinct usernames in past hour</td></tr>\n<tr><td>9</td><td>unique_servers_1h</td><td>Integer</td><td>Distinct targets from this IP</td></tr>\n<tr><td>10</td><td>failure_rate_24h</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Failed/total attempts ratio (0-1)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>11</td><td>consecutive_failures</td><td>Integer</td><td>Sequential failures without success</td></tr>\n<tr><td>12</td><td>time_since_last</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Seconds since last attempt</td></tr>\n<tr><td>13</td><td>is_new_ip</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if first time seeing this IP</td></tr>\n<tr><td>14</td><td>attempts_last_hour</td><td>Integer</td><td>Total attempts in past hour</td></tr>\n<tr><td>15</td><td>success_rate_lifetime</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Historical success rate (0-1)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>A.3 Geographic Features (6)</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>#</th><th>Feature Name</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>16</td><td>country_risk_score</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Risk rating for source country (0-1)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>17</td><td>is_high_risk_country</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if CN, RU, KP, IR, etc.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>18</td><td>distance_from_normal</td><td>Continuous</td><td>km from typical login locations</td></tr>\n<tr><td>19</td><td>is_new_country</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if first login from this country</td></tr>\n<tr><td>20</td><td>timezone_deviation</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Hours from expected timezone</td></tr>\n<tr><td>21</td><td>continent_code</td><td>Categorical</td><td>Continent (AF, AS, EU, NA, SA, OC)</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>A.4 Network Features (8)</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>#</th><th>Feature Name</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>22</td><td>is_proxy</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if VPN/Proxy detected</td></tr>\n<tr><td>23</td><td>is_tor</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if Tor exit node</td></tr>\n<tr><td>24</td><td>is_datacenter</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if hosting provider IP</td></tr>\n<tr><td>25</td><td>asn_risk_score</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Risk associated with ASN (0-1)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>26</td><td>abuse_confidence</td><td>Continuous</td><td>AbuseIPDB confidence (0-100)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>27</td><td>vt_malicious</td><td>Integer</td><td>VirusTotal malicious detections</td></tr>\n<tr><td>28</td><td>abuse_reports_count</td><td>Integer</td><td>Total abuse reports for IP</td></tr>\n<tr><td>29</td><td>is_known_attacker</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if in threat blocklists</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>A.5 Username Features (6)</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>#</th><th>Feature Name</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>30</td><td>is_system_account</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if root, daemon, bin, etc.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>31</td><td>is_common_target</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if admin, test, guest, etc.</td></tr>\n<tr><td>32</td><td>username_entropy</td><td>Continuous</td><td>Shannon entropy of username</td></tr>\n<tr><td>33</td><td>username_length</td><td>Integer</td><td>Character count</td></tr>\n<tr><td>34</td><td>has_numbers</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if username contains digits</td></tr>\n<tr><td>35</td><td>is_sequential</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if matches pattern like user1, user2</td></tr>\n</table>\n\n<h3>A.6 Event Features (5)</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>#</th><th>Feature Name</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>\n<tr><td>36</td><td>is_failed</td><td>Binary</td><td>1 if authentication failed</td></tr>\n<tr><td>37</td><td>auth_method</td><td>Categorical</td><td>password, publickey, keyboard-interactive</td></tr>\n<tr><td>38</td><td>port_number</td><td>Integer</td><td>SSH port (usually 22)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>39</td><td>event_count_today</td><td>Integer</td><td>Events from this IP today</td></tr>\n<tr><td>40</td><td>event_count_week</td><td>Integer</td><td>Events from this IP this week</td></tr>\n</table>',80,1,1,1,650,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(103,'appendix_b',NULL,'B','Appendix B: API Documentation','<h3>B.1 Authentication</h3>\n<p>All API endpoints require JWT authentication:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nPOST /api/v1/auth/login\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{\n    \"email\": \"admin@example.com\",\n    \"password\": \"secure_password\"\n}\n\nResponse:\n{\n    \"access_token\": \"eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIs...\",\n    \"refresh_token\": \"eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIs...\",\n    \"expires_in\": 900\n}\n</pre>\n\n<h3>B.2 Events API</h3>\n\n<h4>List Events</h4>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nGET /api/v1/events?limit=50&offset=0&event_type=failed\nAuthorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;\n\nResponse:\n{\n    \"events\": [\n        {\n            \"id\": 123,\n            \"timestamp\": \"2024-01-15T10:30:00Z\",\n            \"source_ip\": \"192.168.1.100\",\n            \"username\": \"admin\",\n            \"event_type\": \"failed\",\n            \"risk_score\": 75\n        }\n    ],\n    \"total\": 869,\n    \"page\": 1\n}\n</pre>\n\n<h4>Submit Event (Agent)</h4>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nPOST /api/v1/events/batch\nAuthorization: Bearer &lt;agent_token&gt;\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{\n    \"agent_id\": \"agent-001\",\n    \"events\": [\n        {\n            \"timestamp\": \"2024-01-15T10:30:00Z\",\n            \"source_ip\": \"192.168.1.100\",\n            \"username\": \"admin\",\n            \"event_type\": \"failed\",\n            \"auth_method\": \"password\"\n        }\n    ]\n}\n</pre>\n\n<h3>B.3 Threat Intelligence API</h3>\n\n<h4>IP Lookup</h4>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nGET /api/v1/threats/ip/192.168.1.100\nAuthorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;\n\nResponse:\n{\n    \"ip\": \"192.168.1.100\",\n    \"composite_score\": 75,\n    \"risk_level\": \"high\",\n    \"sources\": {\n        \"abuseipdb\": {\n            \"confidence\": 87,\n            \"reports\": 145,\n            \"last_reported\": \"2024-01-14\"\n        },\n        \"virustotal\": {\n            \"malicious\": 3,\n            \"suspicious\": 1\n        },\n        \"geoip\": {\n            \"country\": \"CN\",\n            \"city\": \"Beijing\",\n            \"isp\": \"China Telecom\"\n        }\n    },\n    \"recommended_action\": \"block\"\n}\n</pre>\n\n<h3>B.4 Blocking API</h3>\n\n<h4>Block IP</h4>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nPOST /api/v1/blocking/block\nAuthorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{\n    \"ip\": \"192.168.1.100\",\n    \"duration_minutes\": 60,\n    \"reason\": \"Exceeded failure threshold\"\n}\n</pre>\n\n<h4>Unblock IP</h4>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nPOST /api/v1/blocking/unblock\nAuthorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;\n\n{\n    \"ip\": \"192.168.1.100\"\n}\n</pre>\n\n<h3>B.5 ML API</h3>\n\n<h4>Get Prediction</h4>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nPOST /api/v1/ml/predict\nAuthorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;\n\n{\n    \"source_ip\": \"192.168.1.100\",\n    \"username\": \"admin\",\n    \"event_type\": \"failed\"\n}\n\nResponse:\n{\n    \"risk_score\": 72,\n    \"is_anomaly\": true,\n    \"confidence\": 0.89,\n    \"top_factors\": [\n        \"High attempt velocity\",\n        \"Username enumeration detected\",\n        \"Non-business hours\"\n    ]\n}\n</pre>',81,1,1,1,500,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(104,'appendix_c',NULL,'C','Appendix C: Installation Guide','<h3>C.1 System Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Operating System:</strong> Ubuntu 20.04+ or Debian 11+</li>\n<li><strong>Python:</strong> 3.9 or higher</li>\n<li><strong>Database:</strong> MySQL 8.0+ or MariaDB 10.5+</li>\n<li><strong>Memory:</strong> 1GB minimum, 2GB recommended</li>\n<li><strong>Storage:</strong> 10GB for database, logs</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>C.2 Quick Installation</h3>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\n# Clone repository\ngit clone https://github.com/yourusername/ssh-guardian.git\ncd ssh-guardian\n\n# Install Python dependencies\npython3 -m venv venv\nsource venv/bin/activate\npip install -r requirements.txt\n\n# Configure environment\ncp .env.example .env\nnano .env  # Edit database credentials\n\n# Initialize database\nmysql -u root -p -e \"CREATE DATABASE ssh_guardian\"\nmysql -u root -p ssh_guardian &lt; dbs/migrations/001_initial_schema.sql\nmysql -u root -p ssh_guardian &lt; dbs/seeds/seed_initial.sql\n\n# Start API server\npython run.py\n</pre>\n\n<h3>C.3 Agent Installation</h3>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\n# On monitored server\ncurl -sSL https://your-server/install-agent.sh | bash\n\n# Or manual installation\npip install ssh-guardian-agent\nssh-guardian-agent configure --api-url https://your-server/api/v1 --api-key YOUR_KEY\nssh-guardian-agent start\n</pre>\n\n<h3>C.4 Production Deployment</h3>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\n# Install Gunicorn\npip install gunicorn\n\n# Create systemd service\nsudo nano /etc/systemd/system/ssh-guardian.service\n\n[Unit]\nDescription=SSH Guardian API\nAfter=network.target mysql.service\n\n[Service]\nUser=sshguardian\nWorkingDirectory=/opt/ssh-guardian\nExecStart=/opt/ssh-guardian/venv/bin/gunicorn -w 4 -b 0.0.0.0:5000 run:app\nRestart=always\n\n[Install]\nWantedBy=multi-user.target\n\n# Enable and start\nsudo systemctl enable ssh-guardian\nsudo systemctl start ssh-guardian\n</pre>\n\n<h3>C.5 Nginx Reverse Proxy</h3>\n<pre class=\"code-block\">\nserver {\n    listen 443 ssl http2;\n    server_name ssh-guardian.example.com;\n\n    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/fullchain.pem;\n    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/privkey.pem;\n\n    location / {\n        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5000;\n        proxy_set_header Host $host;\n        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\n        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;\n        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;\n    }\n}\n</pre>\n\n<h3>C.6 Troubleshooting</h3>\n<table class=\"thesis-table\">\n<tr><th>Issue</th><th>Solution</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Database connection failed</td><td>Verify credentials in .env, check MySQL status</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Agent not connecting</td><td>Check firewall, verify API URL and key</td></tr>\n<tr><td>ML predictions slow</td><td>Ensure Redis is running for caching</td></tr>\n<tr><td>High memory usage</td><td>Reduce batch size, increase pagination</td></tr>\n</table>',82,1,1,1,450,'2025-12-25 10:14:25','2025-12-25 10:14:25'),(105,'ch2_sec9','chapter2','2.9','Literature Summary Matrix','<h2>2.9 Literature Summary Matrix</h2>\n\n<p>This section synthesizes the key literature reviewed in this chapter through a comprehensive comparison matrix. The matrix enables systematic identification of research gaps and establishes the theoretical foundation for the SSH Guardian framework (Cao et al., 2023; Ahmad et al., 2021).</p>\n\n<h3>Table 2.1: Literature Comparison Matrix</h3>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr>\n<th>No.</th>\n<th>Author(s) & Year</th>\n<th>Title</th>\n<th>Research Focus</th>\n<th>Methodology</th>\n<th>Key Findings</th>\n<th>Relevance to SSH Guardian</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>Cao et al. (2023)</td>\n<td>A Comprehensive Survey on SSH Security</td>\n<td>SSH threats and defense mechanisms</td>\n<td>Systematic literature review</td>\n<td>Identified 15 major SSH attack categories; recommended hybrid detection approaches</td>\n<td>HIGH - Provides attack taxonomy for rule design</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>Zhang et al. (2022)</td>\n<td>Analyzing Modern SSH Brute-Force Attack Patterns</td>\n<td>SSH brute-force attack analysis</td>\n<td>Empirical study of 2M+ events</td>\n<td>87% of attacks originate from known malicious IPs; threshold-based detection has 23% false positive rate</td>\n<td>HIGH - Validates need for ML enhancement</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3</td>\n<td>Kumar & Singh (2021)</td>\n<td>SSH Credential Stuffing Attacks</td>\n<td>Credential stuffing detection</td>\n<td>Behavioral analysis</td>\n<td>Credential stuffing distinguishable via timing patterns; username entropy analysis effective</td>\n<td>HIGH - Informed feature engineering</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4</td>\n<td>Ahmad et al. (2021)</td>\n<td>Network IDS: ML and Deep Learning Approaches</td>\n<td>ML algorithms for IDS</td>\n<td>Comparative analysis</td>\n<td>Ensemble methods achieve 98.7% accuracy; feature selection critical for performance</td>\n<td>HIGH - Algorithm selection guidance</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5</td>\n<td>Ferrag et al. (2020)</td>\n<td>Deep Learning for Cyber Security Intrusion Detection</td>\n<td>Deep learning IDS approaches</td>\n<td>Systematic review</td>\n<td>CNNs effective for network traffic; computational cost limits SME adoption</td>\n<td>MEDIUM - Justifies lighter ML approach</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6</td>\n<td>Leevy & Khoshgoftaar (2020)</td>\n<td>Intrusion Detection Models Based on CIC-IDS2018</td>\n<td>IDS dataset analysis</td>\n<td>Big data analysis</td>\n<td>Class imbalance major challenge; SMOTE improves minority class detection</td>\n<td>MEDIUM - Data preprocessing insights</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7</td>\n<td>Xu et al. (2023)</td>\n<td>Isolation Forest-Based Anomaly Detection</td>\n<td>Isolation Forest applications</td>\n<td>Literature survey</td>\n<td>Isolation Forest outperforms traditional methods in high-dimensional data; O(n) complexity suitable for real-time</td>\n<td>HIGH - Primary algorithm justification</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8</td>\n<td>Hariri et al. (2021)</td>\n<td>Extended Isolation Forest</td>\n<td>Isolation Forest improvements</td>\n<td>Algorithm development</td>\n<td>Extended IF reduces bias in clustered data; 15% accuracy improvement over standard IF</td>\n<td>HIGH - Algorithm enhancement options</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>Liu & Zhou (2022)</td>\n<td>Adaptive Isolation Forest for Network IDS</td>\n<td>Adaptive anomaly detection</td>\n<td>Experimental validation</td>\n<td>Adaptive threshold improves detection in concept drift scenarios; 12% false positive reduction</td>\n<td>HIGH - Adaptive threshold design</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>Tounsi & Rais (2020)</td>\n<td>Survey on Technical Threat Intelligence</td>\n<td>Threat intelligence integration</td>\n<td>Systematic review</td>\n<td>API-based integration most effective; caching reduces latency by 70%</td>\n<td>HIGH - API integration architecture</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>Schlette & Bohm (2021)</td>\n<td>Measuring Quality of Threat Intelligence Sources</td>\n<td>Threat intelligence quality</td>\n<td>Quantitative analysis</td>\n<td>AbuseIPDB reliability 94.2%; VirusTotal multi-engine approach reduces false positives</td>\n<td>HIGH - API selection validation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>Li & Chen (2023)</td>\n<td>Real-Time Threat Intelligence Integration</td>\n<td>Real-time TI integration</td>\n<td>System implementation</td>\n<td>Asynchronous integration maintains sub-second response; rate limiting essential</td>\n<td>HIGH - Integration architecture</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>Thakkar & Lohiya (2022)</td>\n<td>Survey on Intrusion Detection Systems</td>\n<td>Comprehensive IDS survey</td>\n<td>Systematic review</td>\n<td>Hybrid approaches 15% more effective than single-method; feature selection critical</td>\n<td>HIGH - Hybrid architecture justification</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>Sarker et al. (2020)</td>\n<td>IntruDTree: ML Cyber Security Intrusion Detection</td>\n<td>Decision tree-based IDS</td>\n<td>Experimental study</td>\n<td>Tree-based models interpretable for security analysts; 96.8% detection rate</td>\n<td>MEDIUM - Interpretability considerations</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>Yang et al. (2023)</td>\n<td>Hybrid ML Approaches for Intrusion Detection</td>\n<td>Hybrid IDS review</td>\n<td>Comprehensive review</td>\n<td>Rule-ML combination optimal for zero-day detection; reduces false positives by 35%</td>\n<td>HIGH - Three-layer architecture design</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>Bada & Nurse (2020)</td>\n<td>Cybersecurity for SMEs</td>\n<td>SME cybersecurity challenges</td>\n<td>Survey study</td>\n<td>67% of SMEs lack dedicated security staff; cost-effective solutions essential</td>\n<td>HIGH - Target user validation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td>Osborn & Simpson (2020)</td>\n<td>Risk and Small-Scale Cyber Security</td>\n<td>SME security decision-making</td>\n<td>Qualitative study</td>\n<td>SMEs prioritize ease of deployment; open-source preferred for budget constraints</td>\n<td>HIGH - Design requirements</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>2.9.1 Synthesis of Literature Findings</h3>\n\n<p>The literature matrix reveals several critical insights that directly inform the SSH Guardian design:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Finding 1: Hybrid Detection Superiority</strong><br/>\nMultiple studies (Yang et al., 2023; Thakkar & Lohiya, 2022) demonstrate that hybrid approaches combining rule-based and ML detection achieve 15-35% better performance than single-method solutions. This finding validates the SSH Guardian three-layer architecture.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Finding 2: Isolation Forest Suitability</strong><br/>\nResearch by Xu et al. (2023), Hariri et al. (2021), and Liu & Zhou (2022) consistently identifies Isolation Forest as optimal for network anomaly detection due to its O(n) complexity, unsupervised nature, and effectiveness with high-dimensional data.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Finding 3: Threat Intelligence Value</strong><br/>\nSchlette & Bohm (2021) quantify AbuseIPDB reliability at 94.2%, while Li & Chen (2023) demonstrate sub-second integration latency with proper caching. These findings justify SSH Guardian\'s API integration strategy.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Finding 4: SME Requirements</strong><br/>\nBada & Nurse (2020) and Osborn & Simpson (2020) establish that 67% of SMEs lack dedicated security staff and prioritize cost-effective, easy-to-deploy solutions. SSH Guardian\'s open-source model directly addresses these constraints.</p>\n\n<h3>2.9.2 Research Gap Identification</h3>\n\n<p>Analysis of the literature matrix identifies the following gaps that SSH Guardian addresses:</p>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr>\n<th>Gap ID</th>\n<th>Description</th>\n<th>Source Evidence</th>\n<th>SSH Guardian Solution</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>G1</td>\n<td>No open-source SSH-specific ML-enhanced IDS</td>\n<td>Ahmad et al. (2021); Ferrag et al. (2020)</td>\n<td>Open-source implementation with ML module</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>G2</td>\n<td>Limited threat intelligence integration in SSH tools</td>\n<td>Tounsi & Rais (2020); Li & Chen (2023)</td>\n<td>Multi-API integration (AbuseIPDB, VirusTotal, Shodan)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>G3</td>\n<td>Fail2ban lacks ML capabilities</td>\n<td>Zhang et al. (2022)</td>\n<td>Fail2ban hybrid mode with ML scoring</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>G4</td>\n<td>Commercial solutions too expensive for SMEs</td>\n<td>Bada & Nurse (2020); Osborn & Simpson (2020)</td>\n<td>Free, open-source deployment</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>',21,2,1,1,1450,'2025-12-25 10:46:52','2025-12-25 10:46:52'),(106,'ch3_sec9','chapter3','3.9','Technology Selection and Justification','<h2>3.9 Technology Selection and Justification</h2>\n\n<p>This section documents the systematic technology selection process for SSH Guardian, following Design Science Research principles (Hevner et al., 2004). Each technology choice is justified against alternatives based on requirements derived from the literature review.</p>\n\n<h3>3.9.1 Hardware Requirements</h3>\n\n<p>SSH Guardian is designed to operate on commodity hardware suitable for SME environments (Bada & Nurse, 2020; Osborn & Simpson, 2020).</p>\n\n<h4>Table 3.6: Hardware Specifications and Justification</h4>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr>\n<th>Component</th>\n<th>Minimum Requirement</th>\n<th>Recommended</th>\n<th>Justification</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>CPU</td>\n<td>2 cores @ 2.0 GHz</td>\n<td>4 cores @ 2.5 GHz</td>\n<td>ML inference requires multi-core processing; Isolation Forest O(n) complexity manageable on modest hardware (Xu et al., 2023)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>RAM</td>\n<td>4 GB</td>\n<td>8 GB</td>\n<td>ML model loaded in memory (~500MB); Flask workers require 256MB each; database buffer pool 1GB recommended</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Storage</td>\n<td>20 GB SSD</td>\n<td>50 GB SSD</td>\n<td>Database growth ~1GB/month with 10K events/day; SSD required for MySQL I/O performance</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Network</td>\n<td>100 Mbps</td>\n<td>1 Gbps</td>\n<td>API calls to threat intelligence services; real-time event streaming</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.9.2 Software Technology Selection</h3>\n\n<h4>Table 3.7: Backend Technology Justification</h4>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr>\n<th>Component</th>\n<th>Selected</th>\n<th>Alternatives Considered</th>\n<th>Selection Rationale</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Programming Language</td>\n<td>Python 3.11</td>\n<td>Go, Java, Node.js</td>\n<td>Native scikit-learn support for ML; extensive security libraries; rapid development for research prototype (Ahmad et al., 2021)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Web Framework</td>\n<td>Flask 3.0</td>\n<td>Django, FastAPI, Express</td>\n<td>Lightweight (~15KB); sufficient for API backend; compatible with Gunicorn for production; well-documented</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>WSGI Server</td>\n<td>Gunicorn</td>\n<td>uWSGI, Waitress</td>\n<td>Industry standard for Flask; simple configuration; supports worker processes for concurrency</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Database</td>\n<td>MySQL 8.0</td>\n<td>PostgreSQL, MongoDB, SQLite</td>\n<td>ACID compliance for security logs; robust indexing for time-series queries; familiar to SME administrators; 65+ table schema support</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Cache</td>\n<td>Redis 7.0</td>\n<td>Memcached, In-memory dict</td>\n<td>Persistence for threat intel cache; pub/sub for real-time updates; atomic operations for rate limiting</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Table 3.8: Machine Learning Technology Justification</h4>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr>\n<th>Component</th>\n<th>Selected</th>\n<th>Alternatives Considered</th>\n<th>Selection Rationale</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>ML Library</td>\n<td>scikit-learn 1.3</td>\n<td>TensorFlow, PyTorch, XGBoost</td>\n<td>Native Isolation Forest implementation; lightweight deployment; no GPU requirement; extensive documentation (Xu et al., 2023)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Algorithm</td>\n<td>Isolation Forest</td>\n<td>One-Class SVM, Autoencoder, LOF</td>\n<td>O(n) training complexity; unsupervised (no labeled attack data required); effective for high-dimensional data; interpretable anomaly scores (Hariri et al., 2021)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Feature Engineering</td>\n<td>Custom Python module</td>\n<td>Featuretools, tsfresh</td>\n<td>Domain-specific features for SSH; 40+ engineered features; real-time extraction capability</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Model Serialization</td>\n<td>joblib</td>\n<td>pickle, ONNX</td>\n<td>Optimized for numpy arrays; compression support; scikit-learn recommended format</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Table 3.9: Frontend and Security Technology Justification</h4>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr>\n<th>Component</th>\n<th>Selected</th>\n<th>Alternatives Considered</th>\n<th>Selection Rationale</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Frontend Framework</td>\n<td>Next.js 14 + React</td>\n<td>Vue.js, Angular, Svelte</td>\n<td>Server-side rendering for security; TypeScript support; industry adoption; component ecosystem</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>UI Library</td>\n<td>Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui</td>\n<td>Bootstrap, Material UI</td>\n<td>Utility-first approach; accessible components; consistent design system; lightweight bundle</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Firewall Integration</td>\n<td>UFW (iptables)</td>\n<td>firewalld, nftables</td>\n<td>Ubuntu default; simple CLI interface; Python subprocess integration; iptables reliability</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Log Monitoring</td>\n<td>Custom Python agent</td>\n<td>Filebeat, Fluentd</td>\n<td>Lightweight footprint; real-time syslog parsing; SSH-specific optimization; direct API integration</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.9.3 Third-Party API Selection</h3>\n\n<h4>Table 3.10: Threat Intelligence API Justification</h4>\n\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;\">\n<thead style=\"background-color: #f0f0f0;\">\n<tr>\n<th>API Service</th>\n<th>Free Tier Limits</th>\n<th>Alternatives</th>\n<th>Selection Rationale</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>AbuseIPDB</td>\n<td>1,000 checks/day</td>\n<td>IPQualityScore, Fraud Guard</td>\n<td>94.2% reliability (Schlette & Bohm, 2021); community-driven data; comprehensive abuse reports; generous free tier</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>VirusTotal</td>\n<td>4 requests/min</td>\n<td>Hybrid Analysis, Joe Sandbox</td>\n<td>Multi-engine analysis (70+ vendors); URL and IP scanning; industry standard; excellent documentation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Shodan</td>\n<td>100 credits/month</td>\n<td>Censys, BinaryEdge</td>\n<td>Port scan detection; service identification; IP history; research license available</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>GeoIP</td>\n<td>MaxMind GeoLite2 (Free)</td>\n<td>IP2Location, ipstack</td>\n<td>Offline database (no API latency); country/city accuracy 99.5%; weekly updates; open license</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h3>3.9.4 Technology Stack Summary</h3>\n\n<p>The selected technology stack aligns with the SME deployment requirements identified in the literature (Bada & Nurse, 2020; Osborn & Simpson, 2020):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Cost-Effective:</strong> All components are open-source or have generous free tiers</li>\n<li><strong>Lightweight:</strong> Runs on commodity hardware (4GB RAM minimum)</li>\n<li><strong>Maintainable:</strong> Python and JavaScript widely understood; extensive documentation</li>\n<li><strong>Secure:</strong> Industry-standard components with active security maintenance</li>\n<li><strong>Scalable:</strong> Horizontal scaling possible through load balancing and database replication</li>\n</ul>',39,2,1,1,1100,'2025-12-25 10:46:52','2025-12-25 10:46:52');
